{"title_page": "Crazy (Willie Nelson song)", "text_new": "{{short description|Willie Nelson song popularized by Patsy Cline}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Crazy\n| cover      = Crazy_-_Patsy_Cline.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Patsy Cline]]\n| album      = [[Showcase (Patsy Cline album)|Showcase]]\n| B-side     = Who Can I Count On?\n| released   = October 16, 1961\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = {{ubl|August 21, 1961<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patsy.nu/ |title=A tribute to Patsy Cline |website=Patsy.nu |date=1996-06-27 |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>|[[Quonset Hut Studio|Bradley Film and Recording Studio]], [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]}}\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[traditional pop]]\n| length     = 2:41\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| writer     = [[Willie Nelson]]\n| producer   = [[Owen Bradley]]\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\"'''Crazy'''\" is a ballad composed by [[Willie Nelson]]. It has been recorded by several artists, most notably by {{anchor|Crazy (Patsy Cline)}}[[Patsy Cline]], whose version was a No. 2 country hit in 1962.<ref>{{cite book\n| first=Ace \n| last= Collins\n| year= 1996\n| title= The Stories Behind Country Music's All-time Greatest: 100 Songs\n| edition= \n| publisher= The Berkeley Publishing Group\n| location=New York\n| pages= 157\u2013159\n| isbn=978-1-57297-072-4 }}</ref>\n\nPartly due to the genre-blending nature of the song, it has been covered by dozens of artists in several genres over the years; nevertheless, the song remains inextricably linked with Cline. Nelson's own version appears on his 1962 debut album ''[[...And Then I Wrote]]''.\n\n== Origin ==\nWith some help from a friend named Oliver English, Nelson wrote the song in early 1961; at the time he was a journeyman singer-songwriter who had written several hits for other artists but had not yet had a significant recording of his own. Nelson originally wrote the song for country singer [[Billy Walker (singer)|Billy Walker]], who turned it down for the same reason [[Roy Drusky]] turned down \"[[I Fall to Pieces]]\" the previous year: that it was \"a girl's song\". The song's eventual success helped launch Nelson as a performer as well as a songwriter.\n\nMusically the song is a jazz-pop ballad with country overtones and a complex melody. The lyrics describe the singer's state of bemusement at the singer's own helpless love for the object of his affection.\n\nInterviewed for the [[Ken Burns]] 2019 American [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] TV miniseries ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]'', Nelson says he originally titled the song \"Stupid\", but changed it after playing it at [[Tootsie's Orchid Lounge]] and getting fan reaction.\n\n== Patsy Cline version ==\n[[Patsy Cline]] was already a country music superstar{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} and looking for material to extend a string of hits.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} She picked it as a follow-up to her previous big hit \"I Fall to Pieces\". \"Crazy\", its complex melody suiting Cline's vocal talent perfectly, was released in late 1961, immediately became another huge hit for Cline and widened the crossover audience she had established with her prior hits. It spent 21 weeks on the chart and eventually became one of her signature tunes. Cline's version is No. 85 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]], becoming the third highest ranked song by a solo female artist, after \"[[Respect (Aretha Franklin song)|Respect]]\" by [[Aretha Franklin]] at #5 and \"[[Walk on By (song)|Walk on By]]\" by [[Dionne Warwick]] at #70.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/patsy-cline-crazy-20110526|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time|publisher=RollingStone.com|accessdate=2014-04-07|date=2011-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Willie Nelson in an interview with [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio|Sirius XM]] [[satellite radio]], he was at [[Tootsie's Orchid Lounge]] and had put his own song \"Crazy\" in the jukebox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JjpqWBnHxEU|title=Willie Nelson on Pitching Crazy to Patsy Cline // Willie's Roadhouse|date=28 April 2017|publisher=[[SiriusXM]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Patsy Cline's husband heard it and wanted to get it to Patsy. They were both drunk, and Willie was reluctant to go, and he even stayed in the car while her husband played it for her. In the end, she recorded it a few weeks later. In another interview, Willie says that the song originally was called \"Stupid\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/willie-nelson-talks-writing-three-hits-in-one-road-trip-on-letterman-20121122|title=Willie Nelson Visits 'Letterman'|publisher=[[rollingstone.com]]|date=2012-11-22}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ellis Nassour's biography ''Patsy Cline'', Nelson, then a struggling songwriter known as Hugh Nelson, was a regular at [[Tootsie's Orchid Lounge]] on Nashville's [[Lower Broadway]], which he frequented with friends [[Kris Kristofferson]] and [[Roger Miller]], both also unknown songwriters at this time. Nelson met Cline's husband Charlie Dick at the bar one evening and pitched the song to him. Dick took the track home and played it for Cline, who absolutely hated it at first because Nelson's demo \"spoke\" the lyrics ahead of and behind the beat; an annoyed Cline remarked that she \"couldn't sing like that\".\n\nHowever, Cline's producer, [[Owen Bradley]], loved the song and arranged it in the ballad form in which it later was recorded. On [[Loretta Lynn]]'s album ''[[I Remember Patsy]]'', Bradley reported that as Cline still was recovering from a recent automobile accident that nearly took her life, she'd had difficulty reaching the high notes of the song on the original production night due to her broken ribs. So after about four hours of trying \u2013 in the days of four songs being recorded in three hours \u2013 they called it a night. A week later, she recorded the lead vocal in one take.\n\nIn the same interview, Lynn remembers the first time Cline performed it at the Grand Ole Opry on crutches, and received three standing ovations. [[Barbara Mandrell]] remembers Cline introducing the song to her audiences live in concert saying <blockquote>All my recent hits have come true in my life. I had a hit out called \"Tra-La-La Triangle\" and people thought about me and Gerald and Charlie. I had another hit out called \"I Fall to Pieces\", and I was in a car wreck. Now I'm really worried because I have a new hit single out, and it's called 'Crazy'.</blockquote>\n\nWillie Nelson stated that Cline's version of \"Crazy\" was his favorite song of his that anybody has recorded because it \"was a lot of magic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2XzGOPwCEeY&t=1947|title=Remembering Patsy|publisher=[[TH Entertainment]]|date=1994-08-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Personnel ===\nThe session personnel included:<ref>http://www.patsycline.info/decca.html</ref>\n* [[Harold Bradley]] &ndash; [[Extended-range bass|6-string electric bass]]\n* [[Owen Bradley]] &ndash; organ\n* Patsy Cline &ndash; lead vocals\n* [[Floyd Cramer]] &ndash; piano\n* [[Buddy Harman]] &ndash; drums\n* [[Walter Haynes]] &ndash; [[steel guitar]]\n* Randy Hughes &ndash; acoustic guitar\n* [[The Jordanaires]] &ndash; backing vocals\n* [[Grady Martin]] &ndash; electric guitar\n* [[Bob Moore]] &ndash; acoustic bass\n\n=== Chart performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1961)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Country Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Easy Listening\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 9\n|-\n| Australian Kent Music Report\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 56\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1987)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| UK Singles Chart <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/10159/patsy-cline/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1987-03-28 |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 79\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1990\u201391)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| Irish Singles Chart \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 14\n|-\n| UK Singles Chart <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/10159/patsy-cline/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1990-12-08 |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 14\n|-\n|}\n\n== LeAnn Rimes version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Crazy\n| cover      = Leanncrazysingle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[LeAnn Rimes]]\n| album      = [[LeAnn Rimes (album)|LeAnn Rimes]]\n| released   = December 28, 1999\n| format     = [[Compact disc single|CD single]], [[music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   = 1997-1998\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[country music|Country]]\n| length     = 2:53\n| label      = [[Curb Records|Curb]]\n| writer     = [[Willie Nelson]]\n| producer   = Wilbur C. Rimes\n| prev_title = [[The Cattle Call|Cattle Call]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[I Need You (LeAnn Rimes song)|I Need You]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n}}\nCountry singer [[LeAnn Rimes]] recorded \"Crazy\" for her [[LeAnn Rimes (album)|self-titled cover album]], released in 1999.  It was released as the second and final single from the album. She also performed this song at the [[White House]] for President [[George W. Bush]] and particularly for [[Laura Bush]], who said it was one of her favorite songs.\n\n=== Track listing ===\n'''Europe Single'''\n# \"Crazy\"\n# \"How Do I Live\" (Extended Mix)\t\n# \"[[Blue (Bill Mack song)|Blue]]\"\n\n=== Chart ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1999)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{Singlechart|UK|36|artist=Leann Rimes|song=Crazy|date=1999-12-18}}\n|}\n\n== Other versions ==\nNotable versions include those recorded by [[Linda Ronstadt]] who reached No. 6 on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s country chart with her version in 1977, [[Julio Iglesias]] (hit in the Netherlands, UK and New Zealand), [[Kenny Rogers]] (Kenny Rogers version is a completely different song he wrote himself), [[The Kills]],  [[Dottie West]], [[Shirley Bassey]], [[Guy Lombardo]], [[Chaka Khan]], [[Don McLean]] (Don McClean's is also a completely different song titled \"Crazy Eyes\") and [[The Waifs]]. (Rogers also wrote and recorded another song with the title \"Crazy\", which topped the charts in 1984 and shouldn't be confused with this one). In 2007, the song was covered by English alternative band [[Apartment (London band)|Apartment]]. Willie Nelson has recorded several versions of the song over the years, including a trio version with [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Diana Krall]].  Additionally, it was covered by the [[Kidneythieves]] and co-released on the ''[[Bride of Chucky]]'' soundtrack.\n\nIn 1980 \"Crazy\" was part of the soundtrack for the Loretta Lynn biography ''[[Coal Miner's Daughter (film)|Coal Miner's Daughter]]'' and was sung by [[Beverly D'Angelo]] who was portraying Patsy Cline.\n\nNorah Jones recorded it live in Chicago at the House of Blues on April 16, 2002.\n\nCanadian country music singer [[Colleen Peterson]] covered the song in 1993. Her version peaked at number 29 on the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Country Tracks chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.2254&type=1&interval=24|title=RPM Country Tracks|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=October 2, 1993|accessdate=September 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518075035/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.2254&type=1&interval=24|archive-date=May 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAustralian singer [[Gina Jeffreys]] covered the song on her album ''[[Old Paint]]'' (2010).\n\nCanadian musician [[Neil Young]] released a cover of this song on his 2014 album ''[[A Letter Home]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/neil-youngs-new-covers-album-available-right-now-surprise-20140418 |title=Neil Young's New Covers Album Available Right Now: Surprise! |last1=Greene |first1=Andy |date=18 April 2014 |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Melinda Schneider]] and [[Beccy Cole]] covered the song on their album ''[[Great Women of Country]]'' (2014).\n\n[[Mary Sarah]] and Willie Nelson performed a duet of the song on the album ''Bridges'' (2014), which peaked at 28 on the country Heat Seekers chart in August 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2014/08/28077-country-album-sales-report-august-13-2014/|title=Country Album Sales Report - August 13, 2014 - RoughStock|first=Roughstock -|last=http://www.roughstock.com|publisher=|date=2014-08-13}}</ref>  Willie Nelson elected to sing the song on ''The Voice'' after hearing a contestant sing the National Anthem and commenting \"she can sing the crap outta that song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2014/07/11/mary-sarah-duets-willie-nelson-dolly-parton/12543997/|title=Mary Sarah duets with Willie Nelson, Dolly Parton, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Slim Richey]] recorded a version of \"Crazy\" with Jitterbug Vipers in Austin, Texas in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/sarah-walter-sharp/crazy1 |title=Crazy with Slim Richey by SarahSharp &#124; Sarah Sharp &#124; Free Listening on SoundCloud |website=Soundcloud.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\n[[Hayden Panettiere]] recorded two versions of \"Crazy\" for ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]'' as her character [[Juliette Barnes]] (who portrays Patsy Cline in a biopic), one in 2014 heard in the episode \"That's Me Without You\" and the other in 2015 as a duet with [[Steven Tyler]] (playing himself) in the episode \"Can't Let Go.\"\n\nCanadian singer Brigitte Boisjoli recorded a version of \"Crazy\" on the album ''Patsy Cline'', on which all songs are from the well-known country musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brigitteboisjoli.ca/ |title=Brigitte Boisjoli officiel Nouvel album Sans regret &#124; |website=Brigitteboisjoli.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\nInfluential 1990s Emo band Mineral recorded a version in 1996 for the ''Band Crazy Vol. 1'' compilation from Bzar records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crankthis.com/mineral.html |title=Mineral |website=Crankthis.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref> The cover also appeared as a bonus track on the band's 2014 release ''Mineral 1994-1998 The Complete Collection''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Mineral-1994-1998-The-Complete-Collection/release/6246984 |title=Mineral - 1994 - 1998: The Complete Collection (CD) at Discogs |website=Discogs.com |date=2014-10-24 |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\nItalian-French singer and former French First Lady [[Carla Bruni]] released a cover version on her 2017 album ''[[French Touch]]'', featuring [[Willie Nelson]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Carla Bruni Releases New Cover \"Crazy\"|first=RJ|last=Frometa|date=September 25, 2017|url=http://ventsmagazine.com/2017/09/25/carla-bruni-releases-new-cover-crazy/|website=[[ventsmagazine.com]]}}</ref>\n\nCanadian singer [[Jessie Reyez]] released an R&B cover of the song on 15 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/hear_jessie_reyez_cover_patsy_clines_crazy|title=Hear Jessie Reyez Cover Patsy Cline's \"Crazy\"|last=Slingerland|first=Calum|date=November 15, 2019|website=[[Exclaim!]]|language=en-ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.secondhandsongs.com/song/13025 SecondHandSongs listing of known covers of \"Crazy\"]\n*[https://www.loc.gov/rr/record/nrpb/registry/essays/CRAZY%20-revised.pdf Library of Congress essay] on Patsy Cline's version and its inclusion in the [[National Recording Registry]].\n\n{{Willie Nelson}}\n{{Patsy Cline singles}}\n{{LeAnn Rimes singles}}\n{{Ray Price}}\n{{Ren\u00e9e Geyer}}\n{{Julio Iglesias}}\n\n[[Category:1961 singles]]\n[[Category:1960s ballads]]\n[[Category:Country ballads]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Patsy Cline songs]]\n[[Category:Willie Nelson songs]]\n[[Category:Dottie West songs]]\n[[Category:Ray Price (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Linda Ronstadt songs]]\n[[Category:LeAnn Rimes songs]]\n[[Category:Ren\u00e9e Geyer songs]]\n[[Category:Colleen Peterson songs]]\n[[Category:Julio Iglesias songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Willie Nelson]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Owen Bradley]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by John Lloyd Miller]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n[[Category:1961 songs]]\n[[Category:Decca Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Willie Nelson song popularized by Patsy Cline}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Crazy\n| cover      = Crazy_-_Patsy_Cline.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Patsy Cline]]\n| album      = [[Showcase (Patsy Cline album)|Showcase]]\n| B-side     = Who Can I Count On?\n| released   = October 16, 1961\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = {{ubl|August 21, 1961<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patsy.nu/ |title=A tribute to Patsy Cline |website=Patsy.nu |date=1996-06-27 |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>|[[Quonset Hut Studio|Bradley Film and Recording Studio]], [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]}}\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[traditional pop]]\n| length     = 2:41\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| writer     = [[Willie Nelson]]\n| producer   = [[Owen Bradley]]\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\"'''Crazy'''\" is a ballad composed by [[Willie Nelson]]. It has been recorded by several artists, most notably by {{anchor|Crazy (Patsy Cline)}}[[Patsy Cline]], whose version was a No. 2 country hit in 1962.<ref>{{cite book\n| first=Ace \n| last= Collins\n| year= 1996\n| title= The Stories Behind Country Music's All-time Greatest: 100 Songs\n| edition= \n| publisher= The Berkeley Publishing Group\n| location=New York\n| pages= 157\u2013159\n| isbn=978-1-57297-072-4 }}</ref>\n\nPartly due to the genre-blending nature of the song, it has been covered by dozens of artists in several genres over the years; nevertheless, the song remains inextricably linked with Cline. Nelson's own version appears on his 1962 debut album ''[[...And Then I Wrote]]''.\n\n== Origin ==\nWith some help from a friend named Oliver English, Nelson wrote the song in early 1961; at the time he was a journeyman singer-songwriter who had written several hits for other artists but had not yet had a significant recording of his own. Nelson originally wrote the song for country singer [[Billy Walker (singer)|Billy Walker]], who turned it down for the same reason [[Roy Drusky]] turned down \"[[I Fall to Pieces]]\" the previous year: that it was \"a girl's song\". The song's eventual success helped launch Nelson as a performer as well as a songwriter.\n\nMusically the song is a jazz-pop ballad with country overtones and a complex melody. The lyrics describe the singer's state of bemusement at the singer's own helpless love for the object of his affection.\n\nInterviewed for the [[Ken Burns]] 2019 American [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] TV miniseries ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]'', Nelson says he originally titled the song \"Stupid\", but changed it after playing it at [[Tootsie's Orchid Lounge]] and getting fan reaction.\n\n== Patsy Cline version ==\n[[Patsy Cline]] was already a country music superstar{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} and looking for material to extend a string of hits.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} She picked it as a follow-up to her previous big hit \"I Fall to Pieces\". \"Crazy\", its complex melody suiting Cline's vocal talent perfectly, was released in late 1961, immediately became another huge hit for Cline and widened the crossover audience she had established with her prior hits. It spent 21 weeks on the chart and eventually became one of her signature tunes. Cline's version is No. 85 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]], becoming the third highest ranked song by a solo female artist, after \"[[Respect (Aretha Franklin song)|Respect]]\" by [[Aretha Franklin]] at #5 and \"[[Walk on By (song)|Walk on By]]\" by [[Dionne Warwick]] at #70.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/patsy-cline-crazy-20110526|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time|publisher=RollingStone.com|accessdate=2014-04-07|date=2011-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Willie Nelson in an interview with [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio|Sirius XM]] [[satellite radio]], he was at [[Tootsie's Orchid Lounge]] and had put his own song \"Crazy\" in the jukebox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JjpqWBnHxEU|title=Willie Nelson on Pitching Crazy to Patsy Cline // Willie's Roadhouse|date=28 April 2017|publisher=[[SiriusXM]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Patsy Cline's husband heard it and wanted to get it to Patsy. They were both drunk, and Willie was reluctant to go, and he even stayed in the car while her husband played it for her. In the end, she recorded it a few weeks later. In another interview, Willie says that the song originally was called \"Stupid\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/willie-nelson-talks-writing-three-hits-in-one-road-trip-on-letterman-20121122|title=Willie Nelson Visits 'Letterman'|publisher=[[rollingstone.com]]|date=2012-11-22}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ellis Nassour's biography ''Patsy Cline'', Nelson, then a struggling songwriter known as Hugh Nelson, was a regular at [[Tootsie's Orchid Lounge]] on Nashville's [[Lower Broadway]], which he frequented with friends [[Kris Kristofferson]] and [[Roger Miller]], both also unknown songwriters at this time. Nelson met Cline's husband Charlie Dick at the bar one evening and pitched the song to him. Dick took the track home and played it for Cline, who absolutely hated it at first because Nelson's demo \"spoke\" the lyrics ahead of and behind the beat; an annoyed Cline remarked that she \"couldn't sing like that\".\n\nHowever, Cline's producer, [[Owen Bradley]], loved the song and arranged it in the ballad form in which it later was recorded. On [[Loretta Lynn]]'s album ''[[I Remember Patsy]]'', Bradley reported that as Cline still was recovering from a recent automobile accident that nearly took her life, she'd had difficulty reaching the high notes of the song on the original production night due to her broken ribs. So after about four hours of trying \u2013 in the days of four songs being recorded in three hours \u2013 they called it a night. A week later, she recorded the lead vocal in one take.\n\nIn the same interview, Lynn remembers the first time Cline performed it at the Grand Ole Opry on crutches, and received three standing ovations. [[Barbara Mandrell]] remembers Cline introducing the song to her audiences live in concert saying <blockquote>All my recent hits have come true in my life. I had a hit out called \"Tra-La-La Triangle\" and people thought about me and Gerald and Charlie. I had another hit out called \"I Fall to Pieces\", and I was in a car wreck. Now I'm really worried because I have a new hit single out, and it's called 'Crazy'.</blockquote>\n\nWillie Nelson stated that Cline's version of \"Crazy\" was his favorite song of his that anybody has recorded because it \"was a lot of magic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2XzGOPwCEeY&t=1947|title=Remembering Patsy|publisher=[[TH Entertainment]]|date=1994-08-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Personnel ===\nThe session personnel included:<ref>http://www.patsycline.info/decca.html</ref>\n* [[Harold Bradley]] &ndash; [[Extended-range bass|6-string electric bass]]\n* [[Owen Bradley]] &ndash; organ\n* Patsy Cline &ndash; lead vocals\n* [[Floyd Cramer]] &ndash; piano\n* [[Buddy Harman]] &ndash; drums\n* [[Walter Haynes]] &ndash; [[steel guitar]]\n* Randy Hughes &ndash; acoustic guitar\n* [[The Jordanaires]] &ndash; backing vocals\n* [[Grady Martin]] &ndash; electric guitar\n* [[Bob Moore]] &ndash; acoustic bass\n\n=== Chart performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1961)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Country Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Easy Listening\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 9\n|-\n| Australian Kent Music Report\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 56\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1987)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| UK Singles Chart <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/10159/patsy-cline/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1987-03-28 |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 79\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1990\u201391)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| Irish Singles Chart \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 14\n|-\n| UK Singles Chart <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/10159/patsy-cline/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1990-12-08 |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 14\n|-\n|}\n\n== LeAnn Rimes version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Crazy\n| cover      = Leanncrazysingle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[LeAnn Rimes]]\n| album      = [[LeAnn Rimes (album)|LeAnn Rimes]]\n| released   = December 28, 1999\n| format     = [[Compact disc single|CD single]], [[music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   = 1997-1998\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[country music|Country]]\n| length     = 2:53\n| label      = [[Curb Records|Curb]]\n| writer     = [[Willie Nelson]]\n| producer   = Wilbur C. Rimes\n| prev_title = [[The Cattle Call|Cattle Call]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[I Need You (LeAnn Rimes song)|I Need You]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n}}\nCountry singer [[LeAnn Rimes]] recorded \"Crazy\" for her [[LeAnn Rimes (album)|self-titled cover album]], released in 1999.  It was released as the second and final single from the album. She also performed this song at the [[White House]] for President [[George W. Bush]] and particularly for [[Laura Bush]], who said it was one of her favorite songs.\n\n=== Track listing ===\n'''Europe Single'''\n# \"Crazy\"\n# \"How Do I Live\" (Extended Mix)\t\n# \"[[Blue (Bill Mack song)|Blue]]\"\n\n=== Chart ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1999)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{Singlechart|UK|36|artist=Leann Rimes|song=Crazy|date=1999-12-18}}\n|}\n\n== Other versions ==\nNotable versions include those recorded by [[Linda Ronstadt]] who reached #6 on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s country chart with her version in 1977, [[Julio Iglesias]] (hit in the Netherlands, UK and New Zealand), [[Kenny Rogers]] (Kenny Rogers version is a completely different song he wrote himself), [[The Kills]],  [[Dottie West]], [[Shirley Bassey]], [[Guy Lombardo]], [[Chaka Khan]], [[Don McLean]] (Don McClean's is also a completely different song titled \"Crazy Eyes\") and [[The Waifs]]. (Rogers also wrote and recorded another song with the title \"Crazy\", which topped the charts in 1984 and shouldn't be confused with this one). In 2007, the song was covered by English alternative band [[Apartment (London band)|Apartment]]. Willie Nelson has recorded several versions of the song over the years, including a trio version with [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Diana Krall]].  Additionally, it was covered by the [[Kidneythieves]] and co-released on the ''[[Bride of Chucky]]'' soundtrack.\n\nIn 1980 \"Crazy\" was part of the soundtrack for the Loretta Lynn biography ''[[Coal Miner's Daughter (film)|Coal Miner's Daughter]]'' and was sung by [[Beverly D'Angelo]] who was portraying Patsy Cline.\n\nNorah Jones recorded it live in Chicago at the House of Blues on April 16, 2002.\n\nCanadian country music singer [[Colleen Peterson]] covered the song in 1993. Her version peaked at number 29 on the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Country Tracks chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.2254&type=1&interval=24|title=RPM Country Tracks|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=October 2, 1993|accessdate=September 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518075035/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.2254&type=1&interval=24|archive-date=May 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAustralian singer [[Gina Jeffreys]] covered the song on her album ''[[Old Paint]]'' (2010).\n\nCanadian musician [[Neil Young]] released a cover of this song on his 2014 album ''[[A Letter Home]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/neil-youngs-new-covers-album-available-right-now-surprise-20140418 |title=Neil Young's New Covers Album Available Right Now: Surprise! |last1=Greene |first1=Andy |date=18 April 2014 |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Melinda Schneider]] and [[Beccy Cole]] covered the song on their album ''[[Great Women of Country]]'' (2014).\n\n[[Mary Sarah]] and Willie Nelson performed a duet of the song on the album ''Bridges'' (2014), which peaked at 28 on the country Heat Seekers chart in August 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2014/08/28077-country-album-sales-report-august-13-2014/|title=Country Album Sales Report - August 13, 2014 - RoughStock|first=Roughstock -|last=http://www.roughstock.com|publisher=|date=2014-08-13}}</ref>  Willie Nelson elected to sing the song on ''The Voice'' after hearing a contestant sing the National Anthem and commenting \"she can sing the crap outta that song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2014/07/11/mary-sarah-duets-willie-nelson-dolly-parton/12543997/|title=Mary Sarah duets with Willie Nelson, Dolly Parton, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Slim Richey]] recorded a version of \"Crazy\" with Jitterbug Vipers in Austin, Texas in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/sarah-walter-sharp/crazy1 |title=Crazy with Slim Richey by SarahSharp &#124; Sarah Sharp &#124; Free Listening on SoundCloud |website=Soundcloud.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\n[[Hayden Panettiere]] recorded two versions of \"Crazy\" for ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]'' as her character [[Juliette Barnes]] (who portrays Patsy Cline in a biopic), one in 2014 heard in the episode \"That's Me Without You\" and the other in 2015 as a duet with [[Steven Tyler]] (playing himself) in the episode \"Can't Let Go.\"\n\nCanadian singer Brigitte Boisjoli recorded a version of \"Crazy\" on the album ''Patsy Cline'', on which all songs are from the well-known country musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brigitteboisjoli.ca/ |title=Brigitte Boisjoli officiel Nouvel album Sans regret &#124; |website=Brigitteboisjoli.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\nInfluential 1990s Emo band Mineral recorded a version in 1996 for the ''Band Crazy Vol. 1'' compilation from Bzar records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crankthis.com/mineral.html |title=Mineral |website=Crankthis.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref> The cover also appeared as a bonus track on the band's 2014 release ''Mineral 1994-1998 The Complete Collection''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Mineral-1994-1998-The-Complete-Collection/release/6246984 |title=Mineral - 1994 - 1998: The Complete Collection (CD) at Discogs |website=Discogs.com |date=2014-10-24 |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\nItalian-French singer and former French First Lady [[Carla Bruni]] released a cover version on her 2017 album ''[[French Touch]]'', featuring [[Willie Nelson]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Carla Bruni Releases New Cover \"Crazy\"|first=RJ|last=Frometa|date=September 25, 2017|url=http://ventsmagazine.com/2017/09/25/carla-bruni-releases-new-cover-crazy/|website=[[ventsmagazine.com]]}}</ref>\n\nCanadian singer [[Jessie Reyez]] released an R&B cover of the song on 15 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/hear_jessie_reyez_cover_patsy_clines_crazy|title=Hear Jessie Reyez Cover Patsy Cline's \"Crazy\"|last=Slingerland|first=Calum|date=November 15, 2019|website=[[Exclaim!]]|language=en-ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.secondhandsongs.com/song/13025 SecondHandSongs listing of known covers of \"Crazy\"]\n*[https://www.loc.gov/rr/record/nrpb/registry/essays/CRAZY%20-revised.pdf Library of Congress essay] on Patsy Cline's version and its inclusion in the [[National Recording Registry]].\n\n{{Willie Nelson}}\n{{Patsy Cline singles}}\n{{LeAnn Rimes singles}}\n{{Ray Price}}\n{{Ren\u00e9e Geyer}}\n{{Julio Iglesias}}\n\n[[Category:1961 singles]]\n[[Category:1960s ballads]]\n[[Category:Country ballads]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Patsy Cline songs]]\n[[Category:Willie Nelson songs]]\n[[Category:Dottie West songs]]\n[[Category:Ray Price (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Linda Ronstadt songs]]\n[[Category:LeAnn Rimes songs]]\n[[Category:Ren\u00e9e Geyer songs]]\n[[Category:Colleen Peterson songs]]\n[[Category:Julio Iglesias songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Willie Nelson]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Owen Bradley]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by John Lloyd Miller]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry record