{"title_page": "Agora (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Agora\n| image          = Agoraposter09.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Teaser poster\n| director       = [[Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]]\n| producer       = Fernando Bovaira<br>\u00c1lvaro Augustin\n| writer         = [[Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]]<br>[[Mateo Gil]]\n| starring       = [[Rachel Weisz]]<br>[[Max Minghella]]<br>[[Oscar Isaac]]\n| music          = [[Dario Marianelli]]\n| cinematography = Xavi Gim\u00e9nez\n| editing        = Nacho Ruiz Capillas\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]<br>[[Newmarket Films]]<br>[[Telecinco Cinema]]<br>[[ZON Lusomundo Audiovisuais]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2009|10|09|df=y}}<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |title=Agora (2009) - Release dates |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1186830/releaseinfo |website=[[Internet Movie Database]]}}</ref><!--WP:FILMRELEASE-->\n| runtime        = 126 minutes\n| country        = Spain <br> Malta <br> Portugal <br> France <br> United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $70 million\n| gross          = $39 million\n}}\n'''''Agora''''' ({{lang-es|\u00c1gora}}) is a 2009 Spanish English-language [[historical drama film]] directed by [[Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]] and written by Amen\u00e1bar and [[Mateo Gil]]. The [[biopic]] stars [[Rachel Weisz]] as [[Hypatia]], a mathematician, philosopher and astronomer in late 4th-century [[Egypt (Roman province)|Roman Egypt]], who investigates the flaws of the [[geocentric]] [[Ptolemaic system]] and the [[heliocentrism|heliocentric]] model that challenges it. Surrounded by religious turmoil and social unrest, Hypatia struggles to save the knowledge of [[classical antiquity]] from destruction. [[Max Minghella]] co-stars as Davus, Hypatia's father's slave, and [[Oscar Isaac]] as Hypatia's student, and later prefect of Alexandria, [[Orestes (prefect)|Orestes]].\n\nThe story uses [[historical fiction]] to highlight the [[relationship between religion and science]] at the time amidst the [[decline of Greco-Roman polytheism]] and the [[Christianization of the Roman Empire]]. The title of the film takes its name from the ''[[agora]]'', a public gathering place in ancient Greece, similar to the Roman ''[[Forum (Roman)|forum]]''. The film was produced by Fernando Bovaira and shot on the island of [[Malta]] from March to June 2008. [[Justin Pollard]], co-author of ''The Rise and Fall of Alexandria'' (2007), was the historical adviser for the film.\n\n''Agora'' was screened out of competition at the [[2009 Cannes Film Festival]] in May, and opened in Spain on 9 October 2009 becoming the highest-grossing film of the year for that country. Although the film had difficulty finding distribution, it was released country by country throughout late 2009 and early 2010. The film received a 53% overall approval rating from [[Rotten Tomatoes]] and seven [[Goya Awards]] in Spain, including Best Original Screenplay. It was awarded the [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation Feature Film Prize]] at the [[Hamptons International Film Festival]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 391 AD, [[History of Alexandria#Late Roman and Byzantine period|Alexandria]] is part of the [[Roman Empire]], and Greek philosopher [[Hypatia]] is a teacher at the [[Platonism|Platonic]] school, where future leaders are educated. Hypatia is the daughter of [[Theon of Alexandria|Theon]], the director of the [[Musaeum]] of Alexandria. Hypatia, her father's [[slave]], Davus, and two of her pupils, [[Orestes (prefect)|Orestes]] and [[Synesius]], are immersed in the changing political and social landscape. She rejects Orestes's love as she prefers to devote herself to science. Davus assists Hypatia in her classes and is interested in science. He is also secretly in love with her.\n\nMeanwhile, social unrest begins challenging the Roman rule of the city as Pagans and Christians come into conflict. When the Christians start defiling the statues of the pagan gods and cause one of their priests to burn in a fire, the pagans, including Orestes and Theon, ambush the Christians. However, in the ensuing battle, the pagans unexpectedly find themselves outnumbered by a large Christian mob. Theon is gravely injured, and Hypatia and the pagans take refuge in the [[Serapeum#Alexandria|Library of the Serapeum]]. The Christian siege of the library ends when an envoy of the Roman Emperor [[Theodosius I]] declares that the pagans are pardoned, but the Christians shall be allowed to take possession of the library. Hypatia and the pagans flee while trying to save the most important [[scroll]]s before the Christians overtake the library and destroy its contents. Davus chooses to join the Christian forces. He later returns with a [[gladius]] and [[sexual assault|sexually assaults]] her, but he begins to sob and offers his sword to her. However, she removes his slave collar and tells him that he is free.\n\nSeveral years later, Orestes, now converted to Christianity, is [[prefect]] of Alexandria. Hypatia continues to investigate the motions of the [[Timeline of discovery of Solar System planets and their moons#Prehistory|Sun, the Moon, the five known \"wanderers\" (planets)]], and the stars. Some Christians ridicule the thinking that [[spherical Earth|the Earth is a sphere]] by arguing that people far from the top would fall off the Earth. When they ask Davus what his opinion is, he avoids conflict by saying that only God knows these things.\n\nHypatia also investigates the [[heliocentrism|heliocentric model]] of the solar system proposed by [[Aristarchus of Samos]] by having an object dropped from the mast of a moving ship which demonstrates that a possible motion of the Earth would not affect the motion, relative to Earth, of a falling object on Earth. However, due to [[Heliocentrism#Religious attitudes to heliocentrism|religious objections against heliocentrism]], the Christians have now forbidden Hypatia to teach at the school. The Christians and the [[Judaism|Jews]] come into violent conflict.\n\nThe leader of the Christians, [[Cyril of Alexandria|Cyril]], views Hypatia as having too much influence over Orestes and stages a public ceremony intended to force Orestes to subjugate her. Hypatia's former pupil, Synesius, now the Bishop of [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrene]], comes to her rescue as a religious authority counterweight but says he cannot help her unless she accepts Christianity; she refuses. Hypatia theorizes that the Earth orbits around the Sun in an [[elliptic orbit]], not a circular orbit, with the Sun at one of the [[focus (geometry)|foci]]. Cyril convinces a mob of Christians that Hypatia is a [[witch]], and they vow to kill her. Davus tries to run ahead to warn Hypatia, but she is captured. They strip Hypatia and are about to skin her alive until Davus persuades the mob otherwise, and they decide to [[stoning|stone]] her instead. When the mob goes outside to collect stones, Davus suffocates her to spare her the pain of being stoned and tells the mob that she fainted. Davus leaves as they begin to stone her.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Rachel Weisz]] as [[Hypatia of Alexandria]]. Weisz was already a fan of Amen\u00e1bar's work when she received the script, and was very interested in the role.<ref name=\"Zona\">{{cite web |title=\"Agora\" entrevista Rachel Weisz |url=https://www.youtube.com/watchv=uKHGdj_NqS4&feature=related |publisher=Zona Trailer }} See also: {{cite web |last=Fine |first=Marshall |authorlink=Marshall fine |date=2010-06-01 |title=The Rachel Weisz theorem |url=http://hollywoodandfine.com/interviews/?p=742 |publisher=hollywoodandfine.com |access-date=2010-06-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605154843/http://hollywoodandfine.com/interviews/?p=742 |archive-date=2010-06-05 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> Although she had not heard of Hypatia before, she felt that her history was still relevant to the contemporary world: \"Really, nothing has changed. I mean, we have huge technological advances and medical advances, but in terms of people killing each other in the name of God, fundamentalism still abounds. And in certain cultures, women are still second-class citizens, and they\u2019re denied education.\"<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |date=2009-05-19 |title=Hypatia, history and a never-ending story |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/articles/2009/05/19/1242498745843.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5qKVbewOE?url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2009/05/19/1242498745843.html?page=fullpage |archivedate=2010-06-08 |url-status = live}}</ref> Weisz wanted to delve more into Hypatia's sexuality and her desires, but Amen\u00e1bar disagreed. She also received science lessons to help inform her depiction of the character.<ref name=\"Zona\" /> At the 2009 Cannes Film Festival, Weisz spoke about her style and approach: \"There's no way we could know how people behave in the 4th century. I imagine they were still human beings with the same emotions as we have now. There are cultural customs, I guess, which were different. We approach the acting style to make the people flesh and blood and to make the acting incredibly naturalistic.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= |title=Rachel Weisz in Cannes for Agora |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mBSioB9L9dw |publisher=Films & Stars}}</ref>\n*[[Max Minghella]] as Davus, Hypatia's father's slave. Davus is in love with Hypatia, but it is an [[unrequited love]], and Davus turns towards Christianity instead. When Hypatia is about to be stoned to death at the end of the film, he decides to suffocate her because he still loves her and doesn't want her to suffer any physical pain. The character of Davus was invented as \"eyes for the audience\" and is not based on any historical account.<ref name=\"HolaTV\">{{cite web |date=2009-10-09 |title=En primicia: Max Minghella y Oscar Isaac, estrellas de '\u00c1gor |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ex9rss2hvBg |publisher=HolaTV.com}}</ref> Minghella grew up in Hampstead, near the same area of North London as Weisz, and found it very easy to work with her.<ref>{{cite web |title=Agora - Max Minghella |date=2009-10-08 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nZ-9ngpDz8s |publisher=Estrenos de Cine}}</ref>\n*[[Oscar Isaac]] as [[Orestes (prefect)|Orestes]]. Student of Hypatia, Orestes is an aristocrat, who like Davus, falls in love with her, and has a strong friendship with Hypatia.<ref name=\"HolaTV\" /> Isaac was familiar with the history of early Christianity during the period represented in the film, but like Weisz, he had not heard of Hypatia before joining the project.<ref>{{cite web |date=2009-10-08 |title=Agora - Oscar Isaac |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ci13WRN2Sws |publisher=Estrenos de Cine}}</ref>\n*Sami Samir as Saint [[Cyril of Alexandria]]\n*Manuel Cauchi as [[Pope Theophilus of Alexandria|Theophilus of Alexandria]], uncle of Cyril\n*[[Ashraf Barhom]] as [[Ammonius (Alexandrian monk)|Ammonius]], a [[parabalani]] [[monk]]\n*[[Michael Lonsdale]] as [[Theon of Alexandria]], father of Hypatia\n*[[Rupert Evans]] as [[Synesius|Synesius of Cyrene]]\n*[[Homayoun Ershadi]] as Aspasius the old slave. He acts as Hypatia's [[research assistant]].\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n{{rquote|right|''It's a movie that challenges the audience in terms of reasoning and trying to get into the story. I kept saying the movie is about astronomy and I wanted to express concepts that we study in school\u2014science, mathematics\u2014that don\u2019t show how fascinating the topic is [the way the subjects are taught in modern education]. I wanted to translate [man\u2019s] fascination with the pursuit of knowledge. I wanted to show astronomy and those who study it in the most appealing way. Those are the real heroes of the movie.''|Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar<ref name=\"Holleran\">{{cite news |last=Holleran |first=Scott |date=2010-05-30 |title=Interview: Alejandro Amenabar on Agora |url=http://www.scottholleran.com/interviews/alejandro-amenabar.htm |publisher=scottholleran.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716020142/http://www.scottholleran.com/interviews/alejandro-amenabar.htm |archivedate=2011-07-16 |url-status = dead|df= |access-date=2010-06-04 }}</ref>}}\n\nAfter Amen\u00e1bar completed ''[[The Sea Inside]]'' (2004), he took a break and traveled to the island of Malta, where he used his free time to [[Amateur astronomy|explore the night sky]]. Seeing the [[Milky Way]] galaxy, Amen\u00e1bar began to discuss astronomy with his friends, speculating about [[extraterrestrial life]] on [[extrasolar planet|other planets]]. He started to research astronomy and came across ''[[Cosmos: A Personal Voyage]]'', by American astronomer [[Carl Sagan]].<ref name=\"Billington\">{{cite news |last=Billington |first=Alex |date=2009-05-26 |title=Cannes Interview: Agora Director Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2009/05/26/cannes-interview-agora-director-alejandro-amenabar/ |publisher=First Showing}} See also: {{cite news |last=Saavedra |first=Mikhail |date=2009-09-18 |title=Alternavox at TIFF: In Conversation with\u2026Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar |url=http://alternavox.net/boxoffice/alternavox-at-tiff-in-conversation-withalejandro-amenabar/ |publisher=Alternavox.net}}</ref> Amen\u00e1bar also studied historical figures such as [[Ptolemy]], [[Copernicus]], [[Johannes Kepler]] and [[Galileo]],<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Goldstein \n |first=Patrick \n |date=2009-05-17 \n |title=At Cannes: Alejandro Amenabar's provocative new historical thriller \n |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2009/05/from-cannes-agora-alejandro-amenabars-provocative-new-historical-thriller.html \n |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706230921/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2009/05/from-cannes-agora-alejandro-amenabars-provocative-new-historical-thriller.html\n |archivedate=2010-07-06\n |url-status = live\n}}</ref> but found himself most interested in the story of [[Hypatia]], a 4th-century Greek astronomer whose history, he felt, was still relevant in the 21st century: \"We realized that this particular time in the world had a lot of connections with our contemporary reality. Then the project became really, really intriguing, because we realized that we could make a movie about the past while actually making a movie about the present.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Germain |first=David |date=2009-05-17 |title=Weisz, Amenabar preach enlightenment with 'Agora' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8512013 |work=[[guardian.co.uk]] |location=London}}</ref>\n\nTo prepare for the task of recreating the ancient city of Alexandria without relying on computer generated imagery, Amen\u00e1bar reviewed older [[sword-and-sandal]] films such as ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956), ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959), and ''[[Pharaoh (film)|Pharaoh]]'' (1966).<ref name=\"Billington\" /> A year before the start of pre-production, designer [[Guy Hendrix Dyas]] spent three weeks with Amen\u00e1bar in Madrid to do some preliminary work on the set designs and the recreation of the ancient city of Alexandria so that previous animations could be generated.\n\nThe film was produced by Fernando Bovaira, with Telecinco Cinema as the primary producer along with Mod Producciones, Himenoptero, and [[Sogecable]] as co-producers.<ref>{{cite news |date=2008-03-13 |title=Agora Starts Shooting Stars |url=http://www.4rfv.co.uk/industrynews.asp?id=73034 |publisher=4RFV.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 17, 2008, on the island of [[Malta]], and was scheduled to last 15 weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rolfe |first=Pamela |date=2008-03-14 |title=Bovaira takes wraps off 'Agora' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i2db2b6662428870c4282dd731ffe4dcb|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> Production designer [[Guy Hendrix Dyas]] used large sets on location instead of computer generated imagery at Amen\u00e1bar's direction.<ref name=\"Olsen\">{{cite news |last=Olsen |first=Mark |date=2010-05-30 |title=Indie Focus: In 'Agora,' a faceoff between faith and science |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/30/entertainment/la-ca-indiefocus-20100530 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The construction of the set employed almost 400 people, and was the largest ever designed on the island. Actor Charles Thake (Hesiquius) suffered minor facial injuries on the set when he collided with extras running during a scene.<ref>{{cite news |last=Vella |first=Matthew |date=2008-04-16 |title=Charles Thake sustains minor injuries on 'Agora' set |url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/2008/04/16/n9.html |publisher=[[Malta Today]]}}</ref> Filming ended in June.<ref name=\"Holleran\" />\n\n==Release==\n''Agora'' premiered at the [[2009 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/10904243/year/2009.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Agora |accessdate=2009-05-17|work=festival-cannes.com}} {{cite web| url=https://www.filmofilia.com/2009/05/18/cannes-2009-agora-world-premiere/| title=Cannes 2009: Agora World Premiere - Reviews | author=Fiona | date=18 May 2009 |work=filmofilia }}</ref> but the film was initially unable to find a domestic distributor due to its large budget and length.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |author2=Sharon Swart |date=2009-10-22 |title=Epic Bow for 'Agora' |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |volume=305 |issue=14 |issn=0011-5509 |page=8 }}</ref> The film also had trouble finding a distributor in both the United States and [[Italy]], although it eventually found distributors in both countries.<ref name=\"cna\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Amabile |first=Flavia |date=2009-07-10 |url=http://www.lastampa.it/_web/CMSTP/tmplrubriche/giornalisti/grubrica.asp?ID_blog=124&ID_articolo=730&ID_sezione=&sezione= |title=Il film che l'Italia non vedr\u00e0 |newspaper=[[La Stampa]] |access-date=2009-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091011050611/http://www.lastampa.it/_web/CMSTP/tmplrubriche/giornalisti/grubrica.asp?ID_blog=124&ID_articolo=730&ID_sezione=&sezione= |archive-date=2009-10-11 |url-status = dead}} See also: [http://ipazia.oknotizie.virgilio.it/go.php?us=316450b1b6c80197 Mikado distribuir\u00e0 \u0091agor\u00e0\u0092 in Italia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722065748/http://ipazia.oknotizie.virgilio.it/go.php?us=316450b1b6c80197 |date=2011-07-22 }}; [http://www.firstshowing.net/2009/11/17/alejandro-amenabars-agora-finally-bought-for-us-distribution/ Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar's Agora Finally Bought for US Distribution]</ref> The North America premiere was held at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] in September, 2009.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=2009-11-18 |title='Agora' Finds Distrib |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |volume=305 |issue=33 |issn=0011-5509 |page=9}}</ref> ''Agora'' opened in [[Spain]] on October 9, 2009, breaking box office records for that country.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hopewell |first=John |author2=Emilio Mayorga |date=2009-10-04 |title='Agora' Reigns in Spain |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |page=5 }} {{cite journal |last=Hopewell |first=John |author2=Emilio Mayorga |date=2009-11-16 |title=Spain B.O. Buoyant |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |page=11 }}</ref> A limited release in the United States began on May 28, 2010, opening on two screens at the Paris Theatre and the Sunshine Cinema in [[New York City]]. The film opened on the [[West Coast of the United States]] on June 4, playing only two screens: at The Landmark theatre in [[Los Angeles]] and at Regal's Westpark 8 in [[Irvine, California|Irvine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newmarketfilms.com/filmDetail.cfm?FID=40 |title=Newmarket Films: Agora |publisher=[[Newmarket Films]]}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nIn March 2010, ''Agora'' was released in [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]]-locked DVD and Blu-ray formats.<ref>[http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Agora-Blu-ray/10747/ Blu-Ray.com release info for Agora]</ref> A Region 1-locked DVD was released October 2010.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Agora-Rachel-Weisz/dp/B003EYVXXW Amazon.com page for Agora]</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n{{rquote|right|''A visually imposing, high-minded epic that ambitiously puts one of the pivotal moments in Western history onscreen for the first time.''|Todd McCarthy, ''Variety''<ref>{{cite journal |last=McCarthy |first=Todd |date=2009-05-25 |title=Agora |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |url=https://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=review&reviewid=VE1117940282&cs=1 |volume= |issue=|issn= |page=16}}</ref>}}\n\nBritish writer and film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar and his film, describing ''Agora'' as \"an ambitious, cerebral and complex movie.... Unlike most toga movies, it doesn't rely on CGI spectacle, but real drama and ideas.\" Bradshaw also applauded Rachel Weisz's role as Hypatia, calling it \"an outstanding performance\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Bradshaw |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Bradshaw |date=2010-04-22 |title=Agora |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/apr/22/agora-review |work=[[guardian.co.uk]] |location=London}}</ref>\nAmerican screenwriter and critic [[Roger Ebert]] liked the film and gave it three stars out of four. He said: \"I went to see ''Agora'' expecting an epic with swords, sandals and sex. I found swords and sandals, some unexpected opinions about sex, and a great deal more.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100721/REVIEWS/100729996/0/SCANNERS|title='Agora' review by Roger Ebert | work=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref>\n\nThe film holds a 52% 'Rotten' rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 87 reviews.<ref name=\"rt\" />\n\n===Response from Christians===\nBefore its release, the distribution company insisted on screening the film at the [[Holy See|Vatican]]. No objections were reported and Vatican officials assisted in some of the religious depictions. According to Amen\u00e1bar, \"There\u2019s one scene in which Cyril reads from [[Pauline Epistles|St. Paul]] and [the Vatican] tried to look for the softest version. In the English version, [it is] taken from the [[Authorized King James Version|King James version]] of the [[Bible]].\"<ref name=\"Holleran\"/> The line is excerpted from {{bibleverse|1 Timothy|2:8-2:12|9}}.<ref>[http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1+timothy%202:8-2:12&version=KJV The film uses a partial paraphrase of 1 Timothy 2:8 - 2:12, King James Version]</ref>\n\nThe Religious Anti-Defamation Observatory (Observatorio Antidifamaci\u00f3n Religiosa), a [[Christianity in Spain|Spanish Catholic]] group, claimed that the film was responsible for \"promoting [[anti-Christian sentiment|hatred of Christians]] and reinforcing false clich\u00e9s about the Catholic Church.\"<ref name=\"cna\">{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/civil_groups_protest_new_antichristian_film|title=Civil groups protest new anti-Christian film|publisher=[[Catholic News Agency]]}} See also: [http://www.oadir.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15&Itemid=33 Observatorio Antidifamaci\u00f3n Religiosa] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013113559/http://www.oadir.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15&Itemid=33 |date=2009-10-13 }}</ref> Michael Ordo\u00f1a of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' acknowledges that the film has been criticized for \"perceived slights against Christians\" but that \"its lack of condemnation of specific dogma makes the film's target seem to be fundamentalism in general\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Ordo\u00f1a |first=Michael |date=2010-06-04 |title=Movie review: 'Agora' shows the true casualty of war|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jun/04/entertainment/la-et-capsules-20100604|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, the New York-based Rev. Philip Grey wrote a positive review of the film and strongly recommended it: \"Christians who see themselves in the fanatic, murderous monks of the film and feel offended need to do some serious soul-searching. (...) Hypatia as depicted in the film is firmly opposed to what, in her time and at her city, is offered&mdash;or rather, imposed by brute force&mdash;under the name of 'Christianity'. Nevertheless, she seems to me far more a follower of the precepts of Christianity than are her persecutors and tormentors. (...) In particular, in watching the deeply moving final scene, her going calmly to her death amidst the jeering mob, I could not help but strongly recall Jesus Christ on his own way to Golgotha\".<ref>Rev. Philip B. Grey, \"Real and perceived Christianity in today's mass media and popular culture\" in 'Positive Christianity Review', Summer 2010 issue, p. 26,29</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Agora'' was [[cinema of Spain|Spain's highest-grossing film]] of 2009, earning over $10.3 million within four days of its release on October 9.<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agora/ |title=Agora |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=October 20, 2012| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091012232946/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agora/| archivedate= 12 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nBased on North American theatre tracking data from [[Rentrak|Rentrak Theatrical]], ''[[indieWIRE]]'' reported that ''Agora'' \"scored the highest per-theater-average of any film in the marketplace\" during the [[Memorial Day]] holiday weekend from May 28 through May 31, just after its U.S. [[limited release]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Knegt |first=Peter |date=2010-06-01 |title=Holiday Box Office: \"Agora,\" \"Micmacs\" Post Decent Debuts; Restored \"Breathless\" Scores (UPDATED) |url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/2010/06/01/holiday_box_office_agora_micmacs_post_decent_debuts_restored_breathless_sco/ |publisher=[[indieWire]] }} For hard data see: {{cite news |last=Klady |first=Leonard |date=2010-05-31 |title=True Grit: The Sands of Tommy |url=http://moviecitynews.com/columnists/klady/2010/100531.html |work=The Weekend Report |publisher=Movie City News |access-date=2010-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811043656/http://moviecitynews.com/columnists/klady/2010/100531.html |archive-date=2010-08-11 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> Despite this very high per-theater average, ''Agora'' was never widely released in the United States. According to [[Box Office Mojo]], its widest release in the United States was just 17 theaters.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=agora.htm |title = Agora (2010) - Weekend Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed over $32.3 million (\u20ac21.4 million) by 1 December 2009, and about $35 million by 1 February 2010. As of 10 January 2011, ''Agora'''s worldwide box office earnings were approximately $39 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=agora.htm |title=Agora (2010) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2013-08-16}}</ref> DVD and Blu-ray sales numbers are not publicly available.\n\n===Accolades===\n''Agora'' was nominated for 13 [[Goya Awards]], winning 7.<ref name=\"Olsen\" /> The film won the [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation Feature Film Prize]] ($25,000 USD) in 2009 at the [[Hamptons International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Hamptons Online|url=http://www.hamptons.com/The-Arts/Hamptons-International-Film-Festival/9133/HIFF-And-Alfred-P.-Sloan-Foundation-Celebrate-Ten.html|title=HIFF And Alfred P. Sloan Foundation Celebrate Ten Years|publisher=Hamptons.com}}{{cite web|author=HIFF|date=2010-05-26|url=http://hamptonsfilmfest.org/special-programs/alfred-p-sloan/|title=Special Screening of Agora with Rachel Weisz|publisher=[[Hamptons International Film Festival]]|access-date=2010-11-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125120400/http://hamptonsfilmfest.org/special-programs/alfred-p-sloan/|archive-date=2010-11-25|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Historical accuracy==\n[[File:Cricau Festival 2013 - Lorica squamata - 2.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|By the fifth century AD, when the film is set, Roman soldiers wore either [[Lorica squamata|scale armor]] (pictured) or [[Lorica hamata|chain mail]], not leather armor as they are shown wearing in the film.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/>]]\n\n{{Interlanguage link|Antonio Mampaso|es}}, a Spanish astrophysicist and one of ''Agora'''s scientific advisors, stated in an interview that \"We know that Hypatia lived in Alexandria in the IV and V centuries CE, until her death in 415. Only three primary sources mention Hypatia of Alexandria, apart from other secondary ones\". He added that none of Hypatia's work has survived but it is thought, from secondary sources, that her main fields of study and work were geometry and astronomy. Mampaso claimed that Hypatia invented the [[hydrometer]], an instrument still in use today, and that probably her father [[Theon of Alexandria]], together with Hypatia, invented the [[astrolabe]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sacrist\u00e1n|first=Enrique|date=2009-10-28|url=http://www.oei.es/divulgacioncientifica/entrevistas_034.htm|title=Antonio Mampaso: 'El mejor legado de Hipatia es su propia historia'|work=Servicio de Informaci\u00f3n y Noticias Cient\u00edficas (SINC)|publisher=[[Organization of Ibero-American States]] (OEI) }}</ref> However, it is generally accepted that the astrolabe had already been invented a couple of centuries earlier, and that the instrument was known to the Greeks before the Christian era.<ref>'It is generally accepted that Greek astrologers, in either the 1st or 2nd centuries BCE, invented the astrolabe', Krebs, 'Groundbreaking Scientific Experiments, Inventions, and Discoveries of the Middle Ages and the Renaissance', p. 196 (2004).</ref><ref>'The invention of the astrolabe is usually attributed to Hipparchus of the second century BC. But there is no firm evidence to support this view. It is however certain that the instrument was well known to the Greeks before the beginning of the Christian era.', Sarma, \u2018The Archaic and the Exotic: studies in the history of Indian astronomical instruments\u2019, p. 241 (2008).</ref> Similarly, the hydrometer was invented before Hypatia, and already known in her time. In this regard, [[Pappus of Alexandria]] was recorded as using the hydrometer before Hypatia was even born. [[Synesius]] sent Hypatia a letter describing a hydrometer, and requesting her to have one constructed for him.<ref>\"Ep. 15 is rather short, but gives interesting information: it contains a detailed description of a hydroscope which Synesius asks Hypatia to order for him in Alexandria, requesting that she herself oversee its construction.\", Kari Vogt, \"The Hierophant of Philosophy\" - Hypatia of Alexandria, Kari Elisabeth Boerresen and Kari Vogt, Women's studies of the Christian and Islamic traditions: ancient, medieval, and Renaissance foremothers, p. 161 (1993).</ref><ref>'For the sake of completeness we must mention that fact that SYNESIOS in his letter to HYPATIA mentions a hydrometer, which according to some was already known in the fourth century AD to PRISCIANUS, that is a century before SYNESIOS and HYPATIA.', Forbes, 'A Short History of the Art of Distillation: from the beginnings up to the death of Cellier Blumenthal', p. 25 (1970).</ref><ref>'In 402, Hypatia receives a letter from the ailing Synesius giving a brief description of what he calls a hydroscope. This is a scientific instrument which was then in common use, although Hypatian is often credited with its invention.', Waithe, 'Ancient women philosophers, 600 B.C.-500 A.D.', p. 192 (1987).</ref> There is no evidence that the historical Hypatia ever studied the [[Heliocentrism|heliocentric model]] proposed by [[Aristarchus of Samos]]<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> or that she ever found any evidence to support it.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/><ref name=\"Theodore\"/>\n\nThe set used in the film is meticulously historically authentic,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> showing a blend of Greek, Roman, and Egyptian architectural styles that would have been fitting to the time period,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> but the costumes are anachronistic.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> The Roman soldiers are shown wearing generic armor and weapons resembling the type used in the first century AD,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> but the film is actually set in the fifth century AD, by which time Roman troops no longer wore leather armor<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> and would have instead worn [[Lorica squamata|scale armor]] or [[Lorica hamata|chain mail]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Kelly & Robert Douglas Smith|last=DeVries|title=Medieval Weapons: An Illustrated History of Their Impact|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2007|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=jdcrsCOB-VcC&lpg=PA24&dq=Lorica%20squamata&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q=Lorica%20squamata&f=false 24\u201327]|isbn=9781851095261}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rubens.anu.edu.au/raid1/student_projects97/armour/scale/scale.html|title=Scale (Lorica Squamata)|publisher=[[Australian National University]]|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film contains a scene, based on the final episode of Carl Sagan's ''Cosmos'', in which Christians burn the \"Great Library of Alexandria\",<ref name=\"Theodore\">{{cite book|last=Theodore|first=Jonathan|date=2016|title=The Modern Cultural Myth of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3QPWDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA183&dq=Hypatia+of+Alexandria+astrolabe+discoveries#v=onepage&q=Hypatia%20of%20Alexandria%20astrolabe%20discoveries&f=false|location=Manchester, England|publisher=Palgrave, Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-56997-4|ref=harv}}</ref> but the historical Library of Alexandria had actually ceased to exist in any recognizable form centuries before Hypatia was even born.<ref name=\"O'Neil\">{{cite news|last=O'Neill|first=Tim.|date=2010-05-20|url=http://armariummagnus.blogspot.com/2010/05/hypatia-and-agora-redux.html|title=Hypatia and Agora Redux=''Armarium Magnum''}}</ref><ref name=\"Theodore\"/> The last references to anyone having held membership in the [[Musaeum|Mouseion]] (the larger research institute which contained the library) date to the 260s AD.<ref name=\"Watts\">{{cite book|last=Watts|first=Edward J.|date=2008|title=City and School in Late Antique Athens and Alexandria|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MKolDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=City+and+School+in+Late+Antique+Athens+and+Alexandria#v=onepage&q=Hypatia&f=false|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles, California|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520258167|ref=harv}}</ref> Theon was the head of a school called the \"Mouseion\",<ref name=\"Watts\"/> but it was a different school named after the Hellenistic Mouseion.<ref name=\"Watts\"/> Although Christians under the decree of the bishop [[Pope Theophilus of Alexandria|Theophilus]] did destroy the [[Serapeum of Alexandria]] in 391 AD,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/><ref name=\"Theodore\"/> which, at one time, had housed scrolls from the Library of Alexandria,<ref name=\"Theodore\"/> the Serapeum probably no longer had any scrolls in it at the time of its destruction, since sources prior to 391 speak of its libraries in the past tense.<ref name=\"Theodore\"/> Also, the Christians completely demolished the Serapeum to the ground, leaving no part of its structure intact;<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> whereas, in the film, they merely knock over all the statues and burn the (probably nonexistent) scrolls.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> ''Agora'' also strongly implies that Hypatia was an atheist,<ref name=\"Theodore\"/> which directly contradicts the historical fact that she was a [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonist]] follower of the teachings of [[Plotinus]], who believed that the goal of philosophy was \"a mystical union with the divine.\"<ref name=\"Theodore\"/>\n\n[[Robert Barron (priest)|Robert Barron]], an American Catholic priest, writes in an article: \"Hypatia was indeed a philosopher and she was indeed killed by a mob in 415, but practically everything else about the story that Gibbon and Sagan and Amen\u00e1bar tell is false\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Barron (priest) |date=2010-05-09| url=http://www.catholicnewworld.com/cnwonline/2010/0509/barron.aspx |title=Christians must resist dangerous silliness of \u2018Agora\u2019|work=[[Catholic New World]]}}</ref> Irene A. Artemi, a doctor of theology at Athens University, states that \"The movie\u2014albeit seemingly not turning against the Christian religion\u2014is in fact portraying the Christians as fundamentalist, obscurantist, ignorant and fanatic\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Artemi|first=Irene A.|date=2010-02-12|url=http://www.impantokratoros.gr/D3C02F38.en.aspx|title=The historical inaccuracies of the movie \"AGORA\" by Alejandro Amenabar|publisher=Orthodoxos Typos}}</ref> Similarly, an atheist blogger Tim O'Neil remarks: \"Over and over again, elements are added to the story that are not in the source material: the destruction of the library, the stoning of the Jews in the theatre, Cyril condemning Hypatia's teaching because she is a woman, the heliocentric \"breakthrough\" and Hypatia's supposed irreligiosity.\"<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Hypatia (novel)|Hypatia]]'' &ndash; an 1853 novel by [[Charles Kingsley]]\n*[[Serapeum of Alexandria]]\n*[[List of historical drama films]]\n*[[List of films set in ancient Rome]]\n*''[[The Name of the Rose]]'', also about destruction of classical writings\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Alter |first=Ethan |date=2010-05-25 |title=Film Review: Agora |url=http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/content_display/reviews/specialty-releases/e3i962c9998ff4ef12f54afb5842f192418 |journal=[[Film Journal International]] }}\n*{{cite news |last=Barron |first=Robert |authorlink = Robert Barron (priest)| date=2010-05-09 |title=Christians must resist dangerous silliness of \u2018Agora\u2019 |url=http://www.catholicnewworld.com/cnwonline/2010/0509/barron.aspx |work=[[Catholic New World]]}}\n*{{cite magazine |last=De Pablos |first=Emiliano |author2=John Hopewell |date=2008-03-13 |title=Weisz, Minghella to star in 'Agora' |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117982343.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}\n*{{cite news |last=Debono |first=Galea |date=2009-05-16 |title=Malta-filmed Agora premieres at Cannes tomorrow |url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20090516/local/malta-filmed-agora-premieres-at-cannes-tomorrow |newspaper=[[Times of Malta]]}}\n*[[Hart, David B.]] [http://www.firstthings.com/onthesquare/2010/06/the-perniciously-persistent-myths-of-hypatia-and-the-great-library \"The Perniciously Persistent Myths of Hypatia and the Great Library,\"] ''[[First Things]]'', June 4, 2010.\n*{{cite news |last=Jacoby |first=Susan |authorlink=Susan Jacoby |date=2010-06-02 |title=Reason is the star of \"Agora\" |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/06/agora_a_rare_movie_with_reason_as_its_star.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}\n*{{cite magazine |last=Lopez |first=John |date=2010-05-28 |title=Agora: The Arthouse Does the Summer Blockbuster |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2010/05/agora-the-arthouse-does-the-summer-blockbuster.html |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Mayer |first=Sophie |date=June 2010 |title=Agora |url= |journal=[[Sight & Sound]] |volume=20 |issue=6 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |page=60}}\n*{{cite news |last=Orange |first=Michelle |date=2010-05-28 |title=Agora Strains to Keep Up With Its Own Staggering Vision |url=http://www.movieline.com/2010/05/review-agora-strains-to-keep-up-with-its-own-staggering-vision.php |publisher=[[Movieline]] |access-date=2010-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601005942/http://www.movieline.com/2010/05/review-agora-strains-to-keep-up-with-its-own-staggering-vision.php |archive-date=2010-06-01 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite book |last=Pollard |first=Justin |authorlink=Justin Pollard |author2=Howard Reid |year=2007 |title=The Rise and Fall of Alexandria: Birthplace of the Modern World |publisher=Penguin Group |isbn=978-0-14-311251-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/risefallofalexan0000poll }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Richeson |first=A. W. |date=November 1940 |title=Hypatia of Alexandria |jstor=3028426 |journal=[[National Mathematics Magazine]] |publisher=[[Mathematical Association of America]] |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=74\u201382 |doi=10.2307/3028426}}\n*{{cite news |last=Rohter |first=Larry |authorlink=Larry Rohter|date=2010-05-21 |title=Science vs. Zealots, 1,500 Years Ago |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/23/movies/23agora.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}\n*{{cite news |last=Scott |first=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott |date=2010-05-28 |title=Love Amid the Togas and the Intolerant |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/28/movies/28agora.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}\n*{{cite magazine |last=Stevens |first=Dana |authorlink=Dana Stevens (critic) |date=2010-05-28 |title=Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar's Agora |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2255229/ |magazine=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}\n*{{cite news |author=UPI |date=2008-05-19 |title=Focus Features acquires epic 'Agora'|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2008/05/19/Focus-Features-acquires-epic-Agora/UPI-50301211237622/ |publisher=[[United Press International]]}}\n*{{cite news |author=A. Zaccuri |date=2010-04-14 |title=Una strana Ipazia illuminista |url=http://www.avvenire.it/Cultura/ipazia+polemiche+zaccuri_201004140924433270000.htm |access-date=2011-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418053047/http://www.avvenire.it/Cultura/ipazia+polemiche+zaccuri_201004140924433270000.htm |archive-date=2010-04-18 |url-status = dead|df= }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.agoralapelicula.com/}}\n*{{IMDb title|1186830|Agora}}\n\n{{Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar}}\n{{Mateo Gil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agora}}\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2000s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s historical films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Films about scientists]]\n[[Category:Films about philosophy]]\n[[Category:Films about Christianity]]\n[[Category:Christianization]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dario Marianelli]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 4th century]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 5th century]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Alexandria]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Egypt]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Films set in classical antiquity]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Films set in libraries]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Malta]]\n[[Category:Persecution of pagans in the late Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Roman Alexandria]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Mateo Gil]]\n[[Category:Spanish films]]\n[[Category:Spanish drama films]]\n[[Category:Spanish epic films]]\n[[Category:Telecinco Cinema films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Hypatia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Agora\n| image          = Agoraposter09.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Teaser poster\n| director       = [[Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]]\n| producer       = Fernando Bovaira<br>\u00c1lvaro Augustin\n| writer         = [[Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]]<br>[[Mateo Gil]]\n| starring       = [[Rachel Weisz]]<br>[[Max Minghella]]<br>[[Oscar Isaac]]\n| music          = [[Dario Marianelli]]\n| cinematography = Xavi Gim\u00e9nez\n| editing        = Nacho Ruiz Capillas\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]<br>[[Newmarket Films]]<br>[[Telecinco Cinema]]<br>[[ZON Lusomundo Audiovisuais]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2009|10|09|df=y}}<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |title=Agora (2009) - Release dates |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1186830/releaseinfo |website=[[Internet Movie Database]]}}</ref><!--WP:FILMRELEASE-->\n| runtime        = 126 minutes\n| country        = Spain <br> Malta <br> Portugal <br> France <br> United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $70 million\n| gross          = $39 million\n}}\n'''''Agora''''' ({{lang-es|\u00c1gora}}) is a 2009 Spanish English-language [[historical drama film]] directed by [[Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]] and written by Amen\u00e1bar and [[Mateo Gil]]. The [[biopic]] stars [[Rachel Weisz]] as [[Hypatia]], a mathematician, philosopher and astronomer in late 4th-century [[Egypt (Roman province)|Roman Egypt]], who investigates the flaws of the [[geocentric]] [[Ptolemaic system]] and the [[heliocentrism|heliocentric]] model that challenges it. Surrounded by religious turmoil and social unrest, Hypatia struggles to save the knowledge of [[classical antiquity]] from destruction. [[Max Minghella]] co-stars as Davus, Hypatia's father's slave, and [[Oscar Isaac]] as Hypatia's student, and later prefect of Alexandria, [[Orestes (prefect)|Orestes]].\n\nThe story uses [[historical fiction]] to highlight the [[relationship between religion and science]] at the time amidst the [[decline of Greco-Roman polytheism]] and the [[Christianization of the Roman Empire]]. The title of the film takes its name from the ''[[agora]]'', a public gathering place in ancient Greece, similar to the Roman ''[[Forum (Roman)|forum]]''. The film was produced by Fernando Bovaira and shot on the island of [[Malta]] from March to June 2008. [[Justin Pollard]], co-author of ''The Rise and Fall of Alexandria'' (2007), was the historical adviser for the film.\n\n''Agora'' was screened out of competition at the [[2009 Cannes Film Festival]] in May, and opened in Spain on 9 October 2009 becoming the highest-grossing film of the year for that country. Although the film had difficulty finding distribution, it was released country by country throughout late 2009 and early 2010. The film received a 53% overall approval rating from [[Rotten Tomatoes]] and seven [[Goya Awards]] in Spain, including Best Original Screenplay. It was awarded the [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation Feature Film Prize]] at the [[Hamptons International Film Festival]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 391 AD, [[History of Alexandria#Late Roman and Byzantine period|Alexandria]] is part of the [[Roman Empire]], and Greek philosopher [[Hypatia]] is a teacher at the [[Platonism|Platonic]] school, where future leaders are educated. Hypatia is the daughter of [[Theon of Alexandria|Theon]], the director of the [[Musaeum]] of Alexandria. Hypatia, her father's [[slave]], Davus, and two of her pupils, [[Orestes (prefect)|Orestes]] and [[Synesius]], are immersed in the changing political and social landscape. She rejects Orestes's love as she prefers to devote herself to science. Davus assists Hypatia in her classes and is interested in science. He is also secretly in love with her.\n\nMeanwhile, social unrest begins challenging the Roman rule of the city as Pagans and Christians come into conflict. When the Christians start defiling the statues of the pagan gods and cause one of their priests to burn in a fire, the pagans, including Orestes and Theon, ambush the Christians. However, in the ensuing battle, the pagans unexpectedly find themselves outnumbered by a large Christian mob. Theon is gravely injured, and Hypatia and the pagans take refuge in the [[Serapeum#Alexandria|Library of the Serapeum]]. The Christian siege of the library ends when an envoy of the Roman Emperor [[Theodosius I]] declares that the pagans are pardoned, but the Christians shall be allowed to take possession of the library. Hypatia and the pagans flee while trying to save the most important [[scroll]]s before the Christians overtake the library and destroy its contents. Davus chooses to join the Christian forces. He later returns with a [[gladius]] and [[sexual assault|sexually assaults]] her, but he begins to sob and offers his sword to her. However, she removes his slave collar and tells him that he is free.\n\nSeveral years later, Orestes, now converted to Christianity, is [[prefect]] of Alexandria. Hypatia continues to investigate the motions of the [[Timeline of discovery of Solar System planets and their moons#Prehistory|Sun, the Moon, the five known \"wanderers\" (planets)]], and the stars. Some Christians ridicule the thinking that [[spherical Earth|the Earth is a sphere]] by arguing that people far from the top would fall off the Earth. When they ask Davus what his opinion is, he avoids conflict by saying that only God knows these things.\n\nHypatia also investigates the [[heliocentrism|heliocentric model]] of the solar system proposed by [[Aristarchus of Samos]] by having an object dropped from the mast of a moving ship which demonstrates that a possible motion of the Earth would not affect the motion, relative to Earth, of a falling object on Earth. However, due to [[Heliocentrism#Religious attitudes to heliocentrism|religious objections against heliocentrism]], the Christians have now forbidden Hypatia to teach at the school. The Christians and the [[Judaism|Jews]] come into violent conflict.\n\nThe leader of the Christians, [[Cyril of Alexandria|Cyril]], views Hypatia as having too much influence over Orestes and stages a public ceremony intended to force Orestes to subjugate her. Hypatia's former pupil, Synesius, now the Bishop of [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrene]], comes to her rescue as a religious authority counterweight but says he cannot help her unless she accepts Christianity; she refuses. Hypatia theorizes that the Earth orbits around the Sun in an [[elliptic orbit]], not a circular orbit, with the Sun at one of the [[focus (geometry)|foci]]. Cyril convinces a mob of Christians that Hypatia is a [[witch]], and they vow to kill her. Davus tries to run ahead to warn Hypatia, but she is captured. They strip Hypatia and are about to skin her alive until Davus persuades the mob otherwise, and they decide to [[stoning|stone]] her instead. When the mob goes outside to collect stones, Davus suffocates her to spare her the pain of being stoned and tells the mob that she fainted. Davus leaves as they begin to stone her.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Rachel Weisz]] as [[Hypatia of Alexandria]]. Weisz was already a fan of Amen\u00e1bar's work when she received the script, and was very interested in the role.<ref name=\"Zona\">{{cite web |title=\"Agora\" entrevista Rachel Weisz |url=https://www.youtube.com/watchv=uKHGdj_NqS4&feature=related |publisher=Zona Trailer }} See also: {{cite web |last=Fine |first=Marshall |authorlink=Marshall fine |date=2010-06-01 |title=The Rachel Weisz theorem |url=http://hollywoodandfine.com/interviews/?p=742 |publisher=hollywoodandfine.com |access-date=2010-06-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605154843/http://hollywoodandfine.com/interviews/?p=742 |archive-date=2010-06-05 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> Although she had not heard of Hypatia before, she felt that her history was still relevant to the contemporary world: \"Really, nothing has changed. I mean, we have huge technological advances and medical advances, but in terms of people killing each other in the name of God, fundamentalism still abounds. And in certain cultures, women are still second-class citizens, and they\u2019re denied education.\"<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |date=2009-05-19 |title=Hypatia, history and a never-ending story |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/articles/2009/05/19/1242498745843.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5qKVbewOE?url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2009/05/19/1242498745843.html?page=fullpage |archivedate=2010-06-08 |url-status = live}}</ref> Weisz wanted to delve more into Hypatia's sexuality and her desires, but Amen\u00e1bar disagreed. She also received science lessons to help inform her depiction of the character.<ref name=\"Zona\" /> At the 2009 Cannes Film Festival, Weisz spoke about her style and approach: \"There's no way we could know how people behave in the 4th century. I imagine they were still human beings with the same emotions as we have now. There are cultural customs, I guess, which were different. We approach the acting style to make the people flesh and blood and to make the acting incredibly naturalistic.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= |title=Rachel Weisz in Cannes for Agora |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mBSioB9L9dw |publisher=Films & Stars}}</ref>\n*[[Max Minghella]] as Davus, Hypatia's father's slave. Davus is in love with Hypatia, but it is an [[unrequited love]], and Davus turns towards Christianity instead. When Hypatia is about to be stoned to death at the end of the film, he decides to suffocate her because he still loves her and doesn't want her to suffer any physical pain. The character of Davus was invented as \"eyes for the audience\" and is not based on any historical account.<ref name=\"HolaTV\">{{cite web |date=2009-10-09 |title=En primicia: Max Minghella y Oscar Isaac, estrellas de '\u00c1gor |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ex9rss2hvBg |publisher=HolaTV.com}}</ref> Minghella grew up in Hampstead, near the same area of North London as Weisz, and found it very easy to work with her.<ref>{{cite web |title=Agora - Max Minghella |date=2009-10-08 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nZ-9ngpDz8s |publisher=Estrenos de Cine}}</ref>\n*[[Oscar Isaac]] as [[Orestes (prefect)|Orestes]]. Student of Hypatia, Orestes is an aristocrat, who like Davus, falls in love with her, and has a strong friendship with Hypatia.<ref name=\"HolaTV\" /> Isaac was familiar with the history of early Christianity during the period represented in the film, but like Weisz, he had not heard of Hypatia before joining the project.<ref>{{cite web |date=2009-10-08 |title=Agora - Oscar Isaac |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ci13WRN2Sws |publisher=Estrenos de Cine}}</ref>\n*Sami Samir as Saint [[Cyril of Alexandria]]\n*Manuel Cauchi as [[Pope Theophilus of Alexandria|Theophilus of Alexandria]], uncle of Cyril\n*[[Ashraf Barhom]] as [[Ammonius (Alexandrian monk)|Ammonius]], a [[parabalani]] [[monk]]\n*[[Michael Lonsdale]] as [[Theon of Alexandria]], father of Hypatia\n*[[Rupert Evans]] as [[Synesius|Synesius of Cyrene]]\n*[[Homayoun Ershadi]] as Aspasius the old slave. He acts as Hypatia's [[research assistant]].\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n{{rquote|right|''It's a movie that challenges the audience in terms of reasoning and trying to get into the story. I kept saying the movie is about astronomy and I wanted to express concepts that we study in school\u2014science, mathematics\u2014that don\u2019t show how fascinating the topic is [the way the subjects are taught in modern education]. I wanted to translate [man\u2019s] fascination with the pursuit of knowledge. I wanted to show astronomy and those who study it in the most appealing way. Those are the real heroes of the movie.''|Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar<ref name=\"Holleran\">{{cite news |last=Holleran |first=Scott |date=2010-05-30 |title=Interview: Alejandro Amenabar on Agora |url=http://www.scottholleran.com/interviews/alejandro-amenabar.htm |publisher=scottholleran.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716020142/http://www.scottholleran.com/interviews/alejandro-amenabar.htm |archivedate=2011-07-16 |url-status = dead|df= |access-date=2010-06-04 }}</ref>}}\n\nAfter Amen\u00e1bar completed ''[[The Sea Inside]]'' (2004), he took a break and traveled to the island of Malta, where he used his free time to [[Amateur astronomy|explore the night sky]]. Seeing the [[Milky Way]] galaxy, Amen\u00e1bar began to discuss astronomy with his friends, speculating about [[extraterrestrial life]] on [[extrasolar planet|other planets]]. He started to research astronomy and came across ''[[Cosmos: A Personal Voyage]]'', by American astronomer [[Carl Sagan]].<ref name=\"Billington\">{{cite news |last=Billington |first=Alex |date=2009-05-26 |title=Cannes Interview: Agora Director Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2009/05/26/cannes-interview-agora-director-alejandro-amenabar/ |publisher=First Showing}} See also: {{cite news |last=Saavedra |first=Mikhail |date=2009-09-18 |title=Alternavox at TIFF: In Conversation with\u2026Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar |url=http://alternavox.net/boxoffice/alternavox-at-tiff-in-conversation-withalejandro-amenabar/ |publisher=Alternavox.net}}</ref> Amen\u00e1bar also studied historical figures such as [[Ptolemy]], [[Copernicus]], [[Johannes Kepler]] and [[Galileo]],<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Goldstein \n |first=Patrick \n |date=2009-05-17 \n |title=At Cannes: Alejandro Amenabar's provocative new historical thriller \n |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2009/05/from-cannes-agora-alejandro-amenabars-provocative-new-historical-thriller.html \n |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706230921/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2009/05/from-cannes-agora-alejandro-amenabars-provocative-new-historical-thriller.html\n |archivedate=2010-07-06\n |url-status = live\n}}</ref> but found himself most interested in the story of [[Hypatia]], a 4th-century Greek astronomer whose history, he felt, was still relevant in the 21st century: \"We realized that this particular time in the world had a lot of connections with our contemporary reality. Then the project became really, really intriguing, because we realized that we could make a movie about the past while actually making a movie about the present.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Germain |first=David |date=2009-05-17 |title=Weisz, Amenabar preach enlightenment with 'Agora' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8512013 |work=[[guardian.co.uk]] |location=London}}</ref>\n\nTo prepare for the task of recreating the ancient city of Alexandria without relying on computer generated imagery, Amen\u00e1bar reviewed older [[sword-and-sandal]] films such as ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956), ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959), and ''[[Pharaoh (film)|Pharaoh]]'' (1966).<ref name=\"Billington\" /> A year before the start of pre-production, designer [[Guy Hendrix Dyas]] spent three weeks with Amen\u00e1bar in Madrid to do some preliminary work on the set designs and the recreation of the ancient city of Alexandria so that previous animations could be generated.\n\nThe film was produced by Fernando Bovaira, with Telecinco Cinema as the primary producer along with Mod Producciones, Himenoptero, and [[Sogecable]] as co-producers.<ref>{{cite news |date=2008-03-13 |title=Agora Starts Shooting Stars |url=http://www.4rfv.co.uk/industrynews.asp?id=73034 |publisher=4RFV.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 17, 2008, on the island of [[Malta]], and was scheduled to last 15 weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rolfe |first=Pamela |date=2008-03-14 |title=Bovaira takes wraps off 'Agora' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i2db2b6662428870c4282dd731ffe4dcb|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> Production designer [[Guy Hendrix Dyas]] used large sets on location instead of computer generated imagery at Amen\u00e1bar's direction.<ref name=\"Olsen\">{{cite news |last=Olsen |first=Mark |date=2010-05-30 |title=Indie Focus: In 'Agora,' a faceoff between faith and science |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/30/entertainment/la-ca-indiefocus-20100530 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The construction of the set employed almost 400 people, and was the largest ever designed on the island. Actor Charles Thake (Hesiquius) suffered minor facial injuries on the set when he collided with extras running during a scene.<ref>{{cite news |last=Vella |first=Matthew |date=2008-04-16 |title=Charles Thake sustains minor injuries on 'Agora' set |url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/2008/04/16/n9.html |publisher=[[Malta Today]]}}</ref> Filming ended in June.<ref name=\"Holleran\" />\n\n==Release==\n''Agora'' premiered at the [[2009 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/10904243/year/2009.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Agora |accessdate=2009-05-17|work=festival-cannes.com}} {{cite web| url=https://www.filmofilia.com/2009/05/18/cannes-2009-agora-world-premiere/| title=Cannes 2009: Agora World Premiere - Reviews | author=Fiona | date=18 May 2009 |work=filmofilia }}</ref> but the film was initially unable to find a domestic distributor due to its large budget and length.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |author2=Sharon Swart |date=2009-10-22 |title=Epic Bow for 'Agora' |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |volume=305 |issue=14 |issn=0011-5509 |page=8 }}</ref> The film also had trouble finding a distributor in both the United States and [[Italy]], although it eventually found distributors in both countries.<ref name=\"cna\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Amabile |first=Flavia |date=2009-07-10 |url=http://www.lastampa.it/_web/CMSTP/tmplrubriche/giornalisti/grubrica.asp?ID_blog=124&ID_articolo=730&ID_sezione=&sezione= |title=Il film che l'Italia non vedr\u00e0 |newspaper=[[La Stampa]] |access-date=2009-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091011050611/http://www.lastampa.it/_web/CMSTP/tmplrubriche/giornalisti/grubrica.asp?ID_blog=124&ID_articolo=730&ID_sezione=&sezione= |archive-date=2009-10-11 |url-status = dead}} See also: [http://ipazia.oknotizie.virgilio.it/go.php?us=316450b1b6c80197 Mikado distribuir\u00e0 \u0091agor\u00e0\u0092 in Italia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722065748/http://ipazia.oknotizie.virgilio.it/go.php?us=316450b1b6c80197 |date=2011-07-22 }}; [http://www.firstshowing.net/2009/11/17/alejandro-amenabars-agora-finally-bought-for-us-distribution/ Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar's Agora Finally Bought for US Distribution]</ref> The North America premiere was held at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] in September, 2009.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=2009-11-18 |title='Agora' Finds Distrib |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |volume=305 |issue=33 |issn=0011-5509 |page=9}}</ref> ''Agora'' opened in [[Spain]] on October 9, 2009, breaking box office records for that country.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hopewell |first=John |author2=Emilio Mayorga |date=2009-10-04 |title='Agora' Reigns in Spain |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |page=5 }} {{cite journal |last=Hopewell |first=John |author2=Emilio Mayorga |date=2009-11-16 |title=Spain B.O. Buoyant |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |page=11 }}</ref> A limited release in the United States began on May 28, 2010, opening on two screens at the Paris Theatre and the Sunshine Cinema in [[New York City]]. The film opened on the [[West Coast of the United States]] on June 4, playing only two screens: at The Landmark theatre in [[Los Angeles]] and at Regal's Westpark 8 in [[Irvine, California|Irvine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newmarketfilms.com/filmDetail.cfm?FID=40 |title=Newmarket Films: Agora |publisher=[[Newmarket Films]]}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nIn March 2010, ''Agora'' was released in [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]]-locked DVD and Blu-ray formats.<ref>[http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Agora-Blu-ray/10747/ Blu-Ray.com release info for Agora]</ref> A Region 1-locked DVD was released October 2010.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Agora-Rachel-Weisz/dp/B003EYVXXW Amazon.com page for Agora]</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n{{rquote|right|''A visually imposing, high-minded epic that ambitiously puts one of the pivotal moments in Western history onscreen for the first time.''|Todd McCarthy, ''Variety''<ref>{{cite journal |last=McCarthy |first=Todd |date=2009-05-25 |title=Agora |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |url=https://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=review&reviewid=VE1117940282&cs=1 |volume= |issue=|issn= |page=16}}</ref>}}\n\nBritish writer and film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar and his film, describing ''Agora'' as \"an ambitious, cerebral and complex movie.... Unlike most toga movies, it doesn't rely on CGI spectacle, but real drama and ideas.\" Bradshaw also applauded Rachel Weisz's role as Hypatia, calling it \"an outstanding performance\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Bradshaw |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Bradshaw |date=2010-04-22 |title=Agora |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/apr/22/agora-review |work=[[guardian.co.uk]] |location=London}}</ref>\nAmerican screenwriter and critic [[Roger Ebert]] liked the film and gave it three stars out of four. He said: \"I went to see ''Agora'' expecting an epic with swords, sandals and sex. I found swords and sandals, some unexpected opinions about sex, and a great deal more.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100721/REVIEWS/100729996/0/SCANNERS|title='Agora' review by Roger Ebert | work=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref>\n\nThe film holds a 52% 'Rotten' rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 87 reviews.<ref name=\"rt\" />\n\n===Response from Christians===\nBefore its release, the distribution company insisted on screening the film at the [[Holy See|Vatican]]. No objections were reported and Vatican officials assisted in some of the religious depictions. According to Amen\u00e1bar, \"There\u2019s one scene in which Cyril reads from [[Pauline Epistles|St. Paul]] and [the Vatican] tried to look for the softest version. In the English version, [it is] taken from the [[Authorized King James Version|King James version]] of the [[Bible]].\"<ref name=\"Holleran\"/> The line is excerpted from {{bibleverse|1 Timothy|2:8-2:12|9}}.<ref>[http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1+timothy%202:8-2:12&version=KJV The film uses a partial paraphrase of 1 Timothy 2:8 - 2:12, King James Version]</ref>\n\nThe Religious Anti-Defamation Observatory (Observatorio Antidifamaci\u00f3n Religiosa), a [[Christianity in Spain|Spanish Catholic]] group, claimed that the film was responsible for \"promoting [[anti-Christian sentiment|hatred of Christians]] and reinforcing false clich\u00e9s about the Catholic Church.\"<ref name=\"cna\">{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/civil_groups_protest_new_antichristian_film|title=Civil groups protest new anti-Christian film|publisher=[[Catholic News Agency]]}} See also: [http://www.oadir.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15&Itemid=33 Observatorio Antidifamaci\u00f3n Religiosa] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013113559/http://www.oadir.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15&Itemid=33 |date=2009-10-13 }}</ref> Michael Ordo\u00f1a of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' acknowledges that the film has been criticized for \"perceived slights against Christians\" but that \"its lack of condemnation of specific dogma makes the film's target seem to be fundamentalism in general\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Ordo\u00f1a |first=Michael |date=2010-06-04 |title=Movie review: 'Agora' shows the true casualty of war|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jun/04/entertainment/la-et-capsules-20100604|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, the New York-based Rev. Philip Grey wrote a positive review of the film and strongly recommended it: \"Christians who see themselves in the fanatic, murderous monks of the film and feel offended need to do some serious soul-searching.(...) Hypatia as depicted in the film is firmly opposed to what, in her time and at her city, is offered&mdash;or rather, imposed by brute force&mdash;under the name of 'Christianity'. Nevertheless, she seems to me far more a follower of the precepts of Christianity than are her persecutors and tormentors.(...) In particular, in watching the deeply moving final scene, her going calmly to her death amidst the jeering mob, I could not help but strongly recall Jesus Christ on his own way to Golgotha\".<ref>Rev. Philip B. Grey, \"Real and perceived Christianity in today's mass media and popular culture\" in 'Positive Christianity Review', Summer 2010 issue, p. 26,29</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Agora'' was [[cinema of Spain|Spain's highest-grossing film]] of 2009, earning over $10.3 million within four days of its release on October 9.<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agora/ |title=Agora |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=October 20, 2012| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091012232946/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agora/| archivedate= 12 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nBased on North American theatre tracking data from [[Rentrak|Rentrak Theatrical]], ''[[indieWIRE]]'' reported that ''Agora'' \"scored the highest per-theater-average of any film in the marketplace\" during the [[Memorial Day]] holiday weekend from May 28 through May 31, just after its U.S. [[limited release]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Knegt |first=Peter |date=2010-06-01 |title=Holiday Box Office: \"Agora,\" \"Micmacs\" Post Decent Debuts; Restored \"Breathless\" Scores (UPDATED) |url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/2010/06/01/holiday_box_office_agora_micmacs_post_decent_debuts_restored_breathless_sco/ |publisher=[[indieWire]] }} For hard data see: {{cite news |last=Klady |first=Leonard |date=2010-05-31 |title=True Grit: The Sands of Tommy |url=http://moviecitynews.com/columnists/klady/2010/100531.html |work=The Weekend Report |publisher=Movie City News |access-date=2010-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811043656/http://moviecitynews.com/columnists/klady/2010/100531.html |archive-date=2010-08-11 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> Despite this very high per-theater average, ''Agora'' was never widely released in the United States. According to [[Box Office Mojo]], its widest release in the United States was just 17 theaters.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=agora.htm |title = Agora (2010) - Weekend Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed over $32.3 million (\u20ac21.4 million) by 1 December 2009, and about $35 million by 1 February 2010. As of 10 January 2011, ''Agora'''s worldwide box office earnings were approximately $39 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=agora.htm |title=Agora (2010) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2013-08-16}}</ref> DVD and Blu-ray sales numbers are not publicly available.\n\n===Accolades===\n''Agora'' was nominated for 13 [[Goya Awards]], winning 7.<ref name=\"Olsen\" /> The film won the [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation Feature Film Prize]] ($25,000 USD) in 2009 at the [[Hamptons International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Hamptons Online|url=http://www.hamptons.com/The-Arts/Hamptons-International-Film-Festival/9133/HIFF-And-Alfred-P.-Sloan-Foundation-Celebrate-Ten.html|title=HIFF And Alfred P. Sloan Foundation Celebrate Ten Years|publisher=Hamptons.com}}{{cite web|author=HIFF|date=2010-05-26|url=http://hamptonsfilmfest.org/special-programs/alfred-p-sloan/|title=Special Screening of Agora with Rachel Weisz|publisher=[[Hamptons International Film Festival]]|access-date=2010-11-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125120400/http://hamptonsfilmfest.org/special-programs/alfred-p-sloan/|archive-date=2010-11-25|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Historical accuracy==\n[[File:Cricau Festival 2013 - Lorica squamata - 2.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|By the fifth century AD, when the film is set, Roman soldiers wore either [[Lorica squamata|scale armor]] (pictured) or [[Lorica hamata|chain mail]], not leather armor as they are shown wearing in the film.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/>]]\n\n{{Interlanguage link|Antonio Mampaso|es}}, a Spanish astrophysicist and one of ''Agora'''s scientific advisors, stated in an interview that \"We know that Hypatia lived in Alexandria in the IV and V centuries CE, until her death in 415. Only three primary sources mention Hypatia of Alexandria, apart from other secondary ones\". He added that none of Hypatia's work has survived but it is thought, from secondary sources, that her main fields of study and work were geometry and astronomy. Mampaso claimed that Hypatia invented the [[hydrometer]], an instrument still in use today, and that probably her father [[Theon of Alexandria]], together with Hypatia, invented the [[astrolabe]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sacrist\u00e1n|first=Enrique|date=2009-10-28|url=http://www.oei.es/divulgacioncientifica/entrevistas_034.htm|title=Antonio Mampaso: 'El mejor legado de Hipatia es su propia historia'|work=Servicio de Informaci\u00f3n y Noticias Cient\u00edficas (SINC)|publisher=[[Organization of Ibero-American States]] (OEI) }}</ref> However, it is generally accepted that the astrolabe had already been invented a couple of centuries earlier, and that the instrument was known to the Greeks before the Christian era.<ref>'It is generally accepted that Greek astrologers, in either the 1st or 2nd centuries BCE, invented the astrolabe', Krebs, 'Groundbreaking Scientific Experiments, Inventions, and Discoveries of the Middle Ages and the Renaissance', p. 196 (2004).</ref><ref>'The invention of the astrolabe is usually attributed to Hipparchus of the second century BC. But there is no firm evidence to support this view. It is however certain that the instrument was well known to the Greeks before the beginning of the Christian era.', Sarma, \u2018The Archaic and the Exotic: studies in the history of Indian astronomical instruments\u2019, p. 241 (2008).</ref> Similarly, the hydrometer was invented before Hypatia, and already known in her time. In this regard, [[Pappus of Alexandria]] was recorded as using the hydrometer before Hypatia was even born. [[Synesius]] sent Hypatia a letter describing a hydrometer, and requesting her to have one constructed for him.<ref>\"Ep. 15 is rather short, but gives interesting information: it contains a detailed description of a hydroscope which Synesius asks Hypatia to order for him in Alexandria, requesting that she herself oversee its construction.\", Kari Vogt, \"The Hierophant of Philosophy\" - Hypatia of Alexandria, Kari Elisabeth Boerresen and Kari Vogt, Women's studies of the Christian and Islamic traditions: ancient, medieval, and Renaissance foremothers, p. 161 (1993).</ref><ref>'For the sake of completeness we must mention that fact that SYNESIOS in his letter to HYPATIA mentions a hydrometer, which according to some was already known in the fourth century AD to PRISCIANUS, that is a century before SYNESIOS and HYPATIA.', Forbes, 'A Short History of the Art of Distillation: from the beginnings up to the death of Cellier Blumenthal', p. 25 (1970).</ref><ref>'In 402, Hypatia receives a letter from the ailing Synesius giving a brief description of what he calls a hydroscope. This is a scientific instrument which was then in common use, although Hypatian is often credited with its invention.', Waithe, 'Ancient women philosophers, 600 B.C.-500 A.D.', p. 192 (1987).</ref> There is no evidence that the historical Hypatia ever studied the [[Heliocentrism|heliocentric model]] proposed by [[Aristarchus of Samos]]<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> or that she ever found any evidence to support it.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/><ref name=\"Theodore\"/>\n\nThe set used in the film is meticulously historically authentic,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> showing a blend of Greek, Roman, and Egyptian architectural styles that would have been fitting to the time period,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> but the costumes are anachronistic.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> The Roman soldiers are shown wearing generic armor and weapons resembling the type used in the first century AD,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> but the film is actually set in the fifth century AD, by which time Roman troops no longer wore leather armor<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> and would have instead worn [[Lorica squamata|scale armor]] or [[Lorica hamata|chain mail]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Kelly & Robert Douglas Smith|last=DeVries|title=Medieval Weapons: An Illustrated History of Their Impact|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2007|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=jdcrsCOB-VcC&lpg=PA24&dq=Lorica%20squamata&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q=Lorica%20squamata&f=false 24\u201327]|isbn=9781851095261}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rubens.anu.edu.au/raid1/student_projects97/armour/scale/scale.html|title=Scale (Lorica Squamata)|publisher=[[Australian National University]]|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film contains a scene, based on the final episode of Carl Sagan's ''Cosmos'', in which Christians burn the \"Great Library of Alexandria\",<ref name=\"Theodore\">{{cite book|last=Theodore|first=Jonathan|date=2016|title=The Modern Cultural Myth of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3QPWDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA183&dq=Hypatia+of+Alexandria+astrolabe+discoveries#v=onepage&q=Hypatia%20of%20Alexandria%20astrolabe%20discoveries&f=false|location=Manchester, England|publisher=Palgrave, Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-56997-4|ref=harv}}</ref> but the historical Library of Alexandria had actually ceased to exist in any recognizable form centuries before Hypatia was even born.<ref name=\"O'Neil\">{{cite news|last=O'Neill|first=Tim.|date=2010-05-20|url=http://armariummagnus.blogspot.com/2010/05/hypatia-and-agora-redux.html|title=Hypatia and Agora Redux=''Armarium Magnum''}}</ref><ref name=\"Theodore\"/> The last references to anyone having held membership in the [[Musaeum|Mouseion]] (the larger research institute which contained the library) date to the 260s AD.<ref name=\"Watts\">{{cite book|last=Watts|first=Edward J.|date=2008|title=City and School in Late Antique Athens and Alexandria|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MKolDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=City+and+School+in+Late+Antique+Athens+and+Alexandria#v=onepage&q=Hypatia&f=false|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles, California|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520258167|ref=harv}}</ref> Theon was the head of a school called the \"Mouseion\",<ref name=\"Watts\"/> but it was a different school named after the Hellenistic Mouseion.<ref name=\"Watts\"/> Although Christians under the decree of the bishop [[Pope Theophilus of Alexandria|Theophilus]] did destroy the [[Serapeum of Alexandria]] in 391 AD,<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/><ref name=\"Theodore\"/> which, at one time, had housed scrolls from the Library of Alexandria,<ref name=\"Theodore\"/> the Serapeum probably no longer had any scrolls in it at the time of its destruction, since sources prior to 391 speak of its libraries in the past tense.<ref name=\"Theodore\"/> Also, the Christians completely demolished the Serapeum to the ground, leaving no part of its structure intact;<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> whereas, in the film, they merely knock over all the statues and burn the (probably nonexistent) scrolls.<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/> ''Agora'' also strongly implies that Hypatia was an atheist,<ref name=\"Theodore\"/> which directly contradicts the historical fact that she was a [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonist]] follower of the teachings of [[Plotinus]], who believed that the goal of philosophy was \"a mystical union with the divine.\"<ref name=\"Theodore\"/>\n\n[[Robert Barron (priest)|Robert Barron]], an American Catholic priest, writes in an article: \"Hypatia was indeed a philosopher and she was indeed killed by a mob in 415, but practically everything else about the story that Gibbon and Sagan and Amen\u00e1bar tell is false\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Barron (priest) |date=2010-05-09| url=http://www.catholicnewworld.com/cnwonline/2010/0509/barron.aspx |title=Christians must resist dangerous silliness of \u2018Agora\u2019|work=[[Catholic New World]]}}</ref> Irene A. Artemi, a doctor of theology at Athens University, states that \"The movie\u2014albeit seemingly not turning against the Christian religion\u2014is in fact portraying the Christians as fundamentalist, obscurantist, ignorant and fanatic\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Artemi|first=Irene A.|date=2010-02-12|url=http://www.impantokratoros.gr/D3C02F38.en.aspx|title=The historical inaccuracies of the movie \"AGORA\" by Alejandro Amenabar|publisher=Orthodoxos Typos}}</ref> Similarly, an atheist blogger Tim O'Neil remarks: \"Over and over again, elements are added to the story that are not in the source material: the destruction of the library, the stoning of the Jews in the theatre, Cyril condemning Hypatia's teaching because she is a woman, the heliocentric \"breakthrough\" and Hypatia's supposed irreligiosity.\"<ref name=\"O'Neil\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Hypatia (novel)|Hypatia]]'' &ndash; an 1853 novel by [[Charles Kingsley]]\n*[[Serapeum of Alexandria]]\n*[[List of historical drama films]]\n*[[List of films set in ancient Rome]]\n*''[[The Name of the Rose]]'', also about destruction of classical writings\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Alter |first=Ethan |date=2010-05-25 |title=Film Review: Agora |url=http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/content_display/reviews/specialty-releases/e3i962c9998ff4ef12f54afb5842f192418 |journal=[[Film Journal International]] }}\n*{{cite news |last=Barron |first=Robert |authorlink = Robert Barron (priest)| date=2010-05-09 |title=Christians must resist dangerous silliness of \u2018Agora\u2019 |url=http://www.catholicnewworld.com/cnwonline/2010/0509/barron.aspx |work=[[Catholic New World]]}}\n*{{cite magazine |last=De Pablos |first=Emiliano |author2=John Hopewell |date=2008-03-13 |title=Weisz, Minghella to star in 'Agora' |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117982343.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}\n*{{cite news |last=Debono |first=Galea |date=2009-05-16 |title=Malta-filmed Agora premieres at Cannes tomorrow |url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20090516/local/malta-filmed-agora-premieres-at-cannes-tomorrow |newspaper=[[Times of Malta]]}}\n*[[Hart, David B.]] [http://www.firstthings.com/onthesquare/2010/06/the-perniciously-persistent-myths-of-hypatia-and-the-great-library \"The Perniciously Persistent Myths of Hypatia and the Great Library,\"] ''[[First Things]]'', June 4, 2010.\n*{{cite news |last=Jacoby |first=Susan |authorlink=Susan Jacoby |date=2010-06-02 |title=Reason is the star of \"Agora\" |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/06/agora_a_rare_movie_with_reason_as_its_star.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}\n*{{cite magazine |last=Lopez |first=John |date=2010-05-28 |title=Agora: The Arthouse Does the Summer Blockbuster |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2010/05/agora-the-arthouse-does-the-summer-blockbuster.html |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Mayer |first=Sophie |date=June 2010 |title=Agora |url= |journal=[[Sight & Sound]] |volume=20 |issue=6 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |page=60}}\n*{{cite news |last=Orange |first=Michelle |date=2010-05-28 |title=Agora Strains to Keep Up With Its Own Staggering Vision |url=http://www.movieline.com/2010/05/review-agora-strains-to-keep-up-with-its-own-staggering-vision.php |publisher=[[Movieline]] |access-date=2010-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601005942/http://www.movieline.com/2010/05/review-agora-strains-to-keep-up-with-its-own-staggering-vision.php |archive-date=2010-06-01 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite book |last=Pollard |first=Justin |authorlink=Justin Pollard |author2=Howard Reid |year=2007 |title=The Rise and Fall of Alexandria: Birthplace of the Modern World |publisher=Penguin Group |isbn=978-0-14-311251-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/risefallofalexan0000poll }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Richeson |first=A. W. |date=November 1940 |title=Hypatia of Alexandria |jstor=3028426 |journal=[[National Mathematics Magazine]] |publisher=[[Mathematical Association of America]] |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=74\u201382 |doi=10.2307/3028426}}\n*{{cite news |last=Rohter |first=Larry |authorlink=Larry Rohter|date=2010-05-21 |title=Science vs. Zealots, 1,500 Years Ago |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/23/movies/23agora.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}\n*{{cite news |last=Scott |first=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott |date=2010-05-28 |title=Love Amid the Togas and the Intolerant |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/28/movies/28agora.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}\n*{{cite magazine |last=Stevens |first=Dana |authorlink=Dana Stevens (critic) |date=2010-05-28 |title=Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar's Agora |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2255229/ |magazine=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}\n*{{cite news |author=UPI |date=2008-05-19 |title=Focus Features acquires epic 'Agora'|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2008/05/19/Focus-Features-acquires-epic-Agora/UPI-50301211237622/ |publisher=[[United Press International]]}}\n*{{cite news |author=A. Zaccuri |date=2010-04-14 |title=Una strana Ipazia illuminista |url=http://www.avvenire.it/Cultura/ipazia+polemiche+zaccuri_201004140924433270000.htm |access-date=2011-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418053047/http://www.avvenire.it/Cultura/ipazia+polemiche+zaccuri_201004140924433270000.htm |archive-date=2010-04-18 |url-status = dead|df= }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.agoralapelicula.com/}}\n*{{IMDb title|1186830|Agora}}\n\n{{Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar}}\n{{Mateo Gil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agora}}\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2000s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s historical films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Films about scientists]]\n[[Category:Films about philosophy]]\n[[Category:Films about Christianity]]\n[[Category:Christianization]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dario Marianelli]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 4th century]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 5th century]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Alexandria]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Egypt]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Films set in classical antiquity]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Films set in libraries]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Malta]]\n[[Category:Persecution of pagans in the late Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Roman Alexandria]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Mateo Gil]]\n[[Category:Spanish films]]\n[[Category:Spanish drama films]]\n[[Category:Spanish epic films]]\n[[Category:Telecinco Cinema films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Hypatia]]\n", "name_user": "Nicholas0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResponse from Christians:spacing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agora_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Brigetta Barrett", "text_new": "{{short description|American high jumper}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = Brigetta Barrett\n| image          = Brigetta Barrett by Augustas Didzgalvis.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n| caption        = Brigetta Barrett at [[2013 World Championships in Athletics]]\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = heir_born\n| nationality    = American\n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1990|12|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Westchester, New York]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{convert|6|ft|0|in|cm|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|140|lb|kg|0}}\n| website        = \n| country        = {{USA}}\n| sport          = [[Track and field]]\n| event          = [[High Jump]]\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = Arizona Wildcats\n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = 2012\n| coach          = Sheldon Blockburger\n| retired        = 2016\n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| show-medals    = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Women's [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|the {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2013 World Championships in Athletics|2013 Moscow]] |[[2013 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade|Shenzhen 2011]] | [[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]}}\n}}\n'''Brigetta Barrett''' (born in [[Westchester, New York]] on December 24, 1990) is a former [[high jump]]er from the [[United States]]. Her biggest success is winning the [[silver medal]] at the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's high jump|2012 Olympic Games]] in [[London]]. She retired in 2016 at the age of 25 before coming back in 2017.\n\n==Early career==\n\nAs a high schooler in 2009, Barrett won the Texas class 5A state championship in the girls high jump.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084907/http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/track-field-year.php?year=2008-2009&= UIL 2008-09 Track & Field State Champions]</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Barrett won the national Championships and [[2011 Summer Universiade|World University Games]] in [[Shenzen, China]], jumping 1.96m, a personal best. She also participated in the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's high jump|Athletics World Championships]] in [[Daegu]], [[South Korea]] where she qualified for the final and placed 10th with 1.93 m\n\n=== 2012 and 2013 : olympic and world silver medals ===\n\nDuring the indoors season Barrett achieved 1.97m in January. She qualified at the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic trials]] by clearing 2.01m only surpassed by [[Chaunt\u00e9 Lowe]]. At the Olympic Games in London however she jumped higher than Lowe and became silver medalist, by jumping 2.03m, a new personal best.\n\nBarrett earned 2013 World Outdoor silver medalist (2.00m/6-6.75). Barrett won 2013 NCAA Indoor Championship - indoor  (1.95m/6-4.75). Barrett won 2013 NCAA Outdoor Championship (1.95m/6-4.75). Barrett was a finalist for the 2013 [[The Bowerman]] award. Earlier that year, she jumped a new World Lead and Personal Best 2.04 m.\n\n===Injuries and retirement (2016)===\n\nBrigetta Barrett who hails from [[Wappingers Falls , NY]] jumped {{height|ft=6|in=4+3/4}} Friday, June 6, 2014 7:00pm at [[Rice University]] Track Stadium.<ref>[http://americantrackleague.com/HoustonMeetInfo.pdf 2014 American Track League - Houston]</ref> Barrett placed third in the high jump in {{T&Fcalc|1.91}} at [[2014 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]] in [[Sacramento, California]]. Struggling with injuries, she decided not to jump and to miss the World Championships in [[Beijing]] in August 2015.\nComing back on the track in February 2016 where she only managed to clear 1.84 m, she decided to retire at the age of 25 and to concentrate herself on her own business. In April 2017, she came back on that decision.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Personal==\nBarrett graduated from [[Duncanville High School]] in [[Duncanville, Texas|Duncanville]], [[Texas]] (2009). Her high jump results earned her a scholarship at the [[University of Arizona]]<ref name=\"arizonawildcats.com\">[http://www.arizonawildcats.com/sports/w-track/mtt/barrett_brigetta00.html Brigetta Barrett Arizona Wildcats bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827140307/http://www.arizonawildcats.com/sports/w-track/mtt/barrett_brigetta00.html |date=August 27, 2012 }}</ref> where she graduated cum laude in May 2013, earning a bachelor's degree in [[theater arts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.arizona.edu/features/brigetta-barrett-named-pac-12-woman-year# |title=Brigetta Barrett Named Pac-12 Woman of the Year on www.arizona.edu |access-date=2013-08-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614164130/http://www.arizona.edu/features/brigetta-barrett-named-pac-12-woman-year# |archive-date=2013-06-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing {{USA}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2011\n|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]\n|[[Daegu]], [[South Korea]]\n|10th\n|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics&nbsp;\u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|1.93 m\n|-\n|[[2011 Summer Universiade|Universiade]]\n|[[Shenzhen]], [[China]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|[[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|1.96 m\n|-\n|2012\n|[[2012 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|[[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|2.03 m\n|-\n|2013\n|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]\n|[[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics&nbsp;\u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|2.00 m\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{World Athletics|241169}}\n* [[USATF]] profile for [http://www.legacy.usatf.org/Athlete-Bios/Brigetta-Barrett.aspx Brigetta Barrett]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120827140307/http://www.arizonawildcats.com/sports/w-track/mtt/barrett_brigetta00.html  Brigetta Barrett] \u2013 University of Arizona athlete profile\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|before={{flagicon|RUS}} [[Anna Chicherova]]|title=[[High jump#Women's Seasons Best (Outdoor)|Women's High Jump Best Year Performance]]|years=2013|after={{flagicon|RUS}} [[Maria Kuchina]]<br>{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Anna Chicherova]]<br>{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Ruth Beitia]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer USA Track & Field 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer Universiade Champions High Jump Women}}\n{{Footer US NC High Jump Women}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrett, Brigetta}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female high jumpers]]\n[[Category:Arizona Wildcats women's track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic track and field athletes of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in track and field]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:People from Duncanville, Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes from Texas]]\n[[Category:Duncanville High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2011 Summer Universiade]]\n[[Category:USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships winners]]\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American high jumper}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = Brigetta Barrett\n| image          = Brigetta Barrett by Augustas Didzgalvis.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n| caption        = Brigetta Barrett at [[2013 World Championships in Athletics]]\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = heir_born\n| nationality    = American\n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1990|12|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Westchester, New York]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{convert|6|ft|0|in|cm|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|140|lb|kg|0}}\n| website        = \n| country        = {{USA}}\n| sport          = [[Track and field]]\n| event          = [[High Jump]]\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = Arizona Wildcats\n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = 2012\n| coach          = Sheldon Blockburger\n| retired        = 2016\n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| show-medals    = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Women's [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|the {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2013 World Championships in Athletics|2013 Moscow]] |[[2013 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade|Shenzhen 2011]] | [[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]}}\n}}\n'''Brigetta Barrett''' (born in [[Westchester, New York]] on December 24, 1990) is a former [[high jump]]er from the [[United States]]. Her biggest success is winning the [[silver medal]] at the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's high jump|2012 Olympic Games]] in [[London]]. She retired in 2016 at the age of 25 before coming back in 2017.\n\n==Early career==\n\nAs a high schooler in 2009, Barrett won the Texas class 5A state championship in the girls high jump.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084907/http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/track-field-year.php?year=2008-2009&= UIL 2008-09 Track & Field State Champions]</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Barrett won the national Championships and [[2011 Summer Universiade|World University Games]] in [[Shenzen, China]], jumping 1.96m, a personal best. She also participated in the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's high jump|Athletics World Championships]] in [[Daegu]], [[South Korea]] where she qualified for the final and placed 10th with 1.93 m\n\n=== 2012 and 2013 : olympic and world silver medals ===\n\nDuring the indoors season Barrett achieved 1.97m in January. She qualified at the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic trials]] by clearing 2.01m only surpassed by [[Chaunt\u00e9 Lowe]]. At the Olympic Games in London however she jumped higher than Lowe and became silver medalist, by jumping 2.03m, a new personal best.\n\nBarrett earned 2013 World Outdoor silver medalist (2.00m/6-6.75). Barrett won 2013 NCAA Indoor Championship - indoor  (1.95m/6-4.75). Barrett won 2013 NCAA Outdoor Championship (1.95m/6-4.75). Barrett was a finalist for the 2013 [[The Bowerman]] award. Earlier that year, she jumped a new World Lead and Personal Best 2.04 m.\n\n===Injuries and retirement (2016)===\n\nBrigetta Barrett who hails from [[Wappingers Falls , NY ]] jumped {{height|ft=6|in=4+3/4}} Friday, June 6, 2014 7:00pm at [[Rice University]] Track Stadium.<ref>[http://americantrackleague.com/HoustonMeetInfo.pdf 2014 American Track League - Houston]</ref> Barrett placed third in the high jump in {{T&Fcalc|1.91}} at [[2014 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]] in [[Sacramento, California]]. Struggling with injuries, she decided not to jump and to miss the World Championships in [[Beijing]] in August 2015.\nComing back on the track in February 2016 where she only managed to clear 1.84 m, she decided to retire at the age of 25 and to concentrate herself on her own business. In April 2017, she came back on that decision.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Personal==\nBarrett graduated from [[Duncanville High School]] in [[Duncanville, Texas|Duncanville]], [[Texas]] (2009). Her high jump results earned her a scholarship at the [[University of Arizona]]<ref name=\"arizonawildcats.com\">[http://www.arizonawildcats.com/sports/w-track/mtt/barrett_brigetta00.html Brigetta Barrett Arizona Wildcats bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827140307/http://www.arizonawildcats.com/sports/w-track/mtt/barrett_brigetta00.html |date=August 27, 2012 }}</ref> where she graduated cum laude in May 2013, earning a bachelor's degree in [[theater arts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.arizona.edu/features/brigetta-barrett-named-pac-12-woman-year# |title=Brigetta Barrett Named Pac-12 Woman of the Year on www.arizona.edu |access-date=2013-08-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614164130/http://www.arizona.edu/features/brigetta-barrett-named-pac-12-woman-year# |archive-date=2013-06-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing {{USA}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2011\n|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]\n|[[Daegu]], [[South Korea]]\n|10th\n|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics&nbsp;\u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|1.93 m\n|-\n|[[2011 Summer Universiade|Universiade]]\n|[[Shenzhen]], [[China]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|[[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|1.96 m\n|-\n|2012\n|[[2012 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|[[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|2.03 m\n|-\n|2013\n|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]\n|[[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics&nbsp;\u2013 Women's high jump|High jump]]\n|2.00 m\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[[International Association of Athletics Federations|IAAF]] profile for [http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/biographies/country=USA/athcode=241169/index.html Brigetta Barrett]\n* [[USATF]] profile for [http://www.legacy.usatf.org/Athlete-Bios/Brigetta-Barrett.aspx Brigetta Barrett]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120827140307/http://www.arizonawildcats.com/sports/w-track/mtt/barrett_brigetta00.html  Brigetta Barrett] \u2013 University of Arizona athlete profile\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|before={{flagicon|RUS}} [[Anna Chicherova]]|title=[[High jump#Women's Seasons Best (Outdoor)|Women's High Jump Best Year Performance]]|years=2013|after={{flagicon|RUS}} [[Maria Kuchina]]<br>{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Anna Chicherova]]<br>{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Ruth Beitia]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer USA Track & Field 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer Universiade Champions High Jump Women}}\n{{Footer US NC High Jump Women}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrett, Brigetta}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female high jumpers]]\n[[Category:Arizona Wildcats women's track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic track and field athletes of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in track and field]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics