, effects, important, largest, salt, types, system, source|url=http://www.waterencyclopedia.com/Re-St/Rivers-Major-World.html}}\n* {{cite book|authorlink=Luna Leopold|author=Luna B. Leopold|title=A View of the River|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1994|id=|isbn=978-0-674-93732-1|oclc=28889034}} \u2014 a non-technical primer on the [[geomorphology]] and [[hydraulics]] of water.\n* {{cite book|last=Middleton|first=Nick|title=Rivers: a very short introduction|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-958867-1}}\n\n{{rivers, streams and springs}}\n{{river morphology}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers| ]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water]]\n[[Category:Fluvial landforms]]\n[[Category:Geomorphology]]\n[[Category:Sedimentology]]\n[[Category:Water streams]]\n", "name_user": "88.110.247.108", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/River"}
{"title_page": "London fiscal surplus", "text_new": "[[File:Net fiscal balance by UK nation and region per capita, 2017-18.png|thumb|upright=1.3|Net fiscal balance by UK nation and region per capita, 2017\u201318]]\nThe '''London fiscal surplus''' is the amount of surplus taxation collected in [[London]], [[England]], above the amount spent on local services. Of all the [[United Kingdom]]'s statistical regions, London runs the highest surplus both in absolute terms and per capita. In the 2017\u201318 [[fiscal year]], London's surplus was  \u00a338.6 billion.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Labour Party]] manifesto for the [[1964 United Kingdom general election]] mentions \"drift to the south\" and relative success of London's economy compared to other parts of the UK as problems to be addressed by the central government. The Labour Party won the election and [[Harold Wilson]]'s government made a requirement that all new government organisations be set up outside London to combat excessive centralization. However, the problem continued to increase.<ref name=\"onlondon\" />\n\nThe London surplus averaged \u00a315 billion between 2000 and 2009<ref>{{cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Greg |title=The Making of a World City: London 1991 to 2021 |date=2014 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-1-118-60972-9 |page=160 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MhTfBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA160&lpg=PA160&dq=London+fiscal+surplus&source=bl&ots=HjjfGygsxP&sig=ACfU3U1c2463lKzFZBghZ1dkV7uGEtB6Ag&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwju1fD5uI7pAhWGsZ4KHRUrANo4ChDoATAGegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=London%20fiscal%20surplus&f=false |language=en}}</ref> and increased by \u00a311 billion between 2015\u201316 and 2017\u201318.<ref name=onlondon>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Dave |title=London's tax support for the wider UK has risen again. What should be done? |url=https://www.onlondon.co.uk/londons-tax-support-for-the-wider-uk-has-risen-again-what-is-to-be-done/ |accessdate=29 April 2020 |work=OnLondon |date=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Surplus==\nIn the 2017\u201318 [[fiscal year]], London's surplus was  \u00a338.6 billion after accounting for its share of UK-wide debt. This is similar to the England-wide surplus of \u00a329.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fiscal Transfers |url=https://www.scotfact.com/fiscal-transfers |website=Scotfact |accessdate=29 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nLondon is one of only three NUTS{{what|date=April 2020}} statistical regions to run a surplus, the others being [[South East England]] and [[East of England]].<ref name=\"public finance\">{{cite web |last1=Rutter |first1=Calum |title=Welsh spending cuts cause deficit reduction, says study |url=https://www.publicfinance.co.uk/news/2019/08/welsh-spending-cuts-cause-deficit-reduction-says-study |website=[[Public Finance (magazine)|Public Finance]] |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=2 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Which parts of the UK have the most money spent on them? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-38077948 |accessdate=29 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political implications==\nThe surplus mostly goes to funding expenditure in less wealthy parts of the United Kingdom, such as northern England. Reducing the [[North\u2013South divide (England)|North\u2013South divide]] via government intervention is popular among both [[left-wing populists]] and parts of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Dave |title=Would penalising London help close the 'north-south divide'? |url=https://www.onlondon.co.uk/would-penalising-london-help-close-the-north-south-divide/ |accessdate=29 April 2020 |work=OnLondon |date=30 January 2019}}</ref> In 2019, leading candidates in the [[2021 London mayoral election|upcoming London mayoral election]] signed a letter expressing support for greater [[fiscal autonomy]] for London and other parts of the UK.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Dave |title=Sadiq Khan and mayoral rivals join plea for devolution boost |url=https://www.onlondon.co.uk/sadiq-khan-and-mayoral-rivals-make-joint-plea-for-devolution-boost/ |accessdate=29 April 2020 |work=OnLondon |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of London]]\n[[Category:Public finance of England]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Net fiscal balance by UK nation and region per capita, 2017-18.png|thumb|upright=1.3|Net fiscal balance by UK nation and region per capita, 2017\u201318]]\nThe '''London fiscal surplus''' is the amount of surplus taxation collected in [[London]] above the amount spent on local services. Of all the United Kingdom's statistical regions, London runs the highest surplus both in absolute terms and per capita. In the 2017\u201318 [[fiscal year]], London's surplus was  \u00a338.6 billion.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Labour Party]] manifesto for the [[1964 United Kingdom general election]] mentions \"drift to the south\" and relative success of London's economy compared to other parts of the UK as problems to be addressed by the central government. The Labour Party won the election and [[Harold Wilson]]'s government made a requirement that all new government organisations be set up outside London to combat excessive centralization. However, the problem continued to increase.<ref name=\"onlondon\" />\n\nThe London surplus averaged \u00a315 billion between 2000 and 2009<ref>{{cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Greg |title=The Making of a World City: London 1991 to 2021 |date=2014 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-1-118-60972-9 |page=160 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MhTfBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA160&lpg=PA160&dq=London+fiscal+surplus&source=bl&ots=HjjfGygsxP&sig=ACfU3U1c2463lKzFZBghZ1dkV7uGEtB6Ag&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwju1fD5uI7pAhWGsZ4KHRUrANo4ChDoATAGegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=London%20fiscal%20surplus&f=false |language=en}}</ref> and increased by \u00a311 billion between 2015\u201316 and 2017\u201318.<ref name=onlondon>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Dave |title=London's 